{"title_page": "Momentum (organisation)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Momentum Movement}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{use British English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox organisation\n| name = Momentum\n| pronounce = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| nickname = \n| named_after = \n| image = Momentum logo (2017).png\n| image_border = \n| size = 220px\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| map = \n| msize = \n| malt = \n| mcaption = \n| map2 = \n| abbreviation = \n| motto = A new kind of politics\n| predecessor = \n| merged = \n| successor = \n| formation = {{start date and age|2015|10|08|df=y}}\n| founder = [[Jon Lansman]]\n| extinction = \n| merger = \n| type = \n| status = \n| purpose = \n| professional_title = \n| headquarters = \n| location_city = [[London]]\n| location_country = England\n| location = [[Finsbury Park (area)|Finsbury Park]]<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/><ref name=\"Vice-secretweapon\"/>\n| coords = \n| region = {{plainlist|\n*[[Great Britain]]\n*''[[Labour International]]''}}\n| services = \n| products = \n| methods = \n| fields = \n| membership = 40,000<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\"/>\n| membership_year = 2019\n| language = \n| owner = \n| sec_gen = \n| leader_title = Chair\n| leader_name = Jon Lansman\n| leader_title2 = Vice-Chair\n| leader_name2 = {{plainlist|\n*Emina Ibrahim\n*Cecile Wright}}\n| leader_title3 = National coordinator\n| leader_name3 = ''Vacant''\n| leader_title4 = Digital officer\n| leader_name4 = \n| board_of_directors = {{plainlist|\n*Jon Lansman\n*[[Sam Tarry]]\n*Anthony Kearns\n*[[Elizabeth Kennedy Hayden|Elizabeth Hayden]]\n*Cecile Wright}}\n| key_people = \n| main_organ = \n| parent_organisation = \n| subsidiaries = \n| affiliations = {{plainlist|class=nowrap|\n*[[Centre-Left Grassroots Alliance]]\n*[[Campaign for Socialism]] (in Scotland)\n*Welsh Labour Grassroots (in Wales)}}\n| budget = \n| budget_year = \n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = \n| disbursements = \n| expenses = \n| expenses_year = \n| endowment = \n| endowment_year = \n| staff = 13<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/>\n| staff_year = 2019\n| volunteers = \n| volunteers_year = \n| website = {{url|https://peoplesmomentum.com/}}\n| remarks = \n| formerly = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Momentum''' is a British political organisation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-controversial-left-wing-group-to-debate-joining-labour-in-boost-to-jeremy-corbyn-a6779916.html|title=Momentum group may join Labour to boost Jeremy Corbyn|last=McTague|first=Tom|date=19 December 2015|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> It has been described as a [[grassroots movement]] supportive of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]],<ref name=bush2015/><ref name=smith2015>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34609114|title=What is Momentum, and why is it worrying Labour MPs?|work=BBC News|date=24 October 2015|author=Norman Smith}}</ref><ref name=\"JonStone 8Oct Indy\">{{cite news|last1=Stone|first1=Jon|title=Jeremy Corbyn's leadership campaign sets up new local activist network called 'Momentum'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyns-leadership-campaign-sets-up-new-local-activist-network-called-momentum-a6686191.html|accessdate=23 November 2015|work=The Independent|date=8 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011181318/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyns-leadership-campaign-sets-up-new-local-activist-network-called-momentum-a6686191.html|archivedate=11 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> it is seen to represent the [[left-wing (politics)|left]] of the party.{{refn|group=n|name=left|\n* {{cite news |date= 23 December 2019 |title= Ed Miliband to join review of Labour's election failure |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50888060 |work= BBC News |access-date= 11 January 2020}}\n* {{cite news |date= 12 December 2019 |title= Corbyn blames Brexit as Labour Party rifts erupt following dismal general election results |url= https://www.itv.com/news/2019-12-12/labour-blame-brexit-dominated-campaign-as-poll-predicts-disastrous-defeat/ |work= ITV News |access-date= 11 January 2020}}\n* <ref name=\"Indy-JohnthankMomentum\"/>\n* {{cite news |last= Wright |first= Oliver |date= 31 July 2018 |title= Labour\u2019s Momentum defeated in founder\u2019s constituency |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/labour-s-momentum-defeated-in-founder-s-constituency-vnfg6svkl |work= The Times |access-date= 11 January 2020}}}}\n\nIt was founded in 2015 by [[Jon Lansman]], Adam Klug, Emma Rees and [[James Schneider]], following the successful campaign for Jeremy Corbyn to become the Leader of the Labour Party. The current officers of Momentum Campaign (Services) Ltd are:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09654873/officers|title=Momentum Campaign (Services) Ltd|publisher=[[Companies House]]|accessdate=2020-01-08}}</ref> Lansman, [[Sam Tarry MP]], [[Mossley Hill (ward)|Mossley Hill]] Councillor [[Elizabeth Kennedy Hayden|Elizabeth Hayden]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whocanivotefor.co.uk/person/43536/elizabeth-kennedy-hayden|title=Elizabeth Kennedy Hayden|publisher=WhoCanIVoteFor?|accessdate=2020-01-08}}</ref> solicitor Anthony Kearns,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://solicitors.lawsociety.org.uk/person/295168/anthony-paul-kearns|title=Anthony Paul Kearns|publisher=[[Law Society]]|accessdate=2020-01-08}}</ref> and Professor Cecile Wright of the [[University of Nottingham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/news/expertiseguide/sociology-social-policy/professor-cecile-yvonne-wright-.aspx|title=Professor Cecile Yvonne Wright |publisher=[[University of Nottingham]]|accessdate=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation has polarised Labour politicians and journalists since its inception. Some have compared it to the [[Militant tendency]] within the Labour party; however, others have praised its grassroots engagement as well as its effective and virally spread but low budget information videos, such as those used in the 2017 general election campaign. Since January 2017, all Momentum members must also be or become members of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"Cowburn110117\"/> The organisation had 40,000 members in 2019.<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\"/> It also has close links with [[The World Transformed]].\n\n== Background ==\nMomentum was founded in 2015 by [[Jon Lansman]] along with the original national organisers, Adam Klug, Emma Rees and [[James Schneider]], four weeks after [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s [[2015 Jeremy Corbyn Labour Party leadership campaign|successful campaign]] for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leadership.<ref name=G8815>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/08/jeremy-corbyn-leadership-campaign-new-social-movement-momentum|title=Jeremy Corbyn leadership campaign gives rise to new social movement|author=Patrick Wintour|date=8 October 2015|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=bush2015>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2015/10/labour-mps-are-worried-about-momentum-should-they-be|title=Labour MPs are worried about Momentum. Should they be?|magazine=New Statesman|date= 23 October 2015|author=Stephen Bush}}</ref><ref name=\"RP-Howitallcametobe\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.redpepper.org.uk/how-momentum-came-together/|title=How Momentum came together|last=Ghadiali|first=Ashish|date=16 January 2018|work=Red Pepper|access-date=}}</ref> Local groups formed in support for Corbyn's leadership, uniting different factions of [[British Left|the left across Britain]] behind the movement to get him elected.<ref name=\"RP-Howitallcametobe\"/> Lansman was active in [[Tony Benn]]'s [[1981 Labour Party deputy leadership election|1981 deputy leadership bid]].<ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/> Beyond their support for Corbyn, Momentum has three primary goals: to win elections for Labour, to create a socialist Labour government, and help build a wider social movement.<ref name=\"Vice-secretweapon\"/> Corbyn was positive about Momentum following its formation, saying in 2016: \u201cI see Momentum as a social movement. A movement that will campaign on all of these issues. But above all, excite and unite people to come together, to come together to challenge injustice, inequality and social exclusion. Bring people together to achieve things together. That is what is makes us [Labour] so different from every other political party in this country.\u201d<ref name=\"HP-Corbynsaysbenice\">{{cite news|last=Simons|first=Ned|title=Jeremy Corbyn tells Momentum to unite amid internal rift as aides plot leadership relaunch|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-corbyn-tells-momentum-disunity-is-our-enemy-amid-internal-rift_uk_5853261ae4b0acb6e4b7d4f1|work=HuffPost|date=16 December 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nWith its formation, Momentum drew inspiration from [[Syriza]] in Greece and [[Podemos (Spanish political party)|Podemos]] in Spain, both of which were fed by practical, grassroots organising to counter the effects of austerity cuts.<ref name=\"RP-Howitallcametobe\"/><ref name=\"theguardian2\">{{cite news |last=Bulman|first=May|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/jun/14/momentum-grassroots-democracy-labour-unstoppable|title=Labour Party membership soars by 35,000 since general election|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=13 June 2017|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> As the movement has evolved, it has also benefited from ideas from other campaigns that operate on a [[left-wing]] or [[Progressivism|progressive]] platform such as in the United States, with the [[Bernie Sanders]] campaign to become presidential candidate for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic party]] in [[Bernie Sanders 2016 presidential campaign|2016]]<ref name=\"GUberniecampaign\"/> and [[Bernie Sanders 2020 presidential campaign|2020]]<ref name=\"GU-DSAsupport\"/> or [[Beto O'Rourke]]'s [[2018 United States Senate election in Texas|campaign to become the Democratic Senator]] for [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/07/momentum-to-examine-texas-us-senate-race-for-tips-for-labour-campaigns |title= Momentum to examine US Senate race for tips for Labour campaigns |author= Dan Sabbagh |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 7 November 2018 |accessdate= 28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Relationship with other organisations ===\nIn 2016 the Scottish left-wing organisation [[Campaign for Socialism]] (CfS) formed a partnership with Momentum. Though they are maintained as separate organisations they share membership and resources. Since then, the membership of CfS has grown from 400 in 2015 to 1,418 by 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rodgers |first1=Sienna |title=Corbynsceptics celebrate as Pam Duncan-Glancy is reselected in Glasgow North |url=https://labourlist.org/2018/05/corbynsceptics-celebrate-as-pam-duncan-glancy-is-reselected-in-glasgow-north/ |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=[[LabourList]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Courea |first1=Eleni |title=\"Momentum needs to reflect the different regions\": Meet the Scottish Corbynites |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2019/05/momentum-needs-reflect-different-regions-meet-scottish-corbynites |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=[[New Statesman]] |language=en}}</ref>\nWelsh Labour Grassroots is the sister organisation of Momentum in Wales.<ref>{{cite news |date= 13 April 2020 |title= Coronavirus: Labour group calls for distinct Welsh response |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52272918 |work= BBC News |access-date= 15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Williamson |first1=David |title=Mark Drakeford tipped to be next Welsh Labour leader |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/mark-drakeford-tipped-next-welsh-14498381 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=walesonline |publisher=[[Reach plc]] |date=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Early infiltration from the far-left ===\n\nMembers of the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] (PLP) had raised concerns that parties on the [[far-left]] of British politics including the [[Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition]], [[Left Unity (UK)|Left Unity]], the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]] (SWP), the [[Socialist Party (England and Wales)|Socialist Party]] and the [[Alliance for Workers' Liberty]] (AWL) might join Momentum as a means to influence the Labour Party.<ref name=\"Guardian: Momentum\">{{cite news|last1 = Wintour|first1 = Patrick|title = Unite challenges expulsion of alleged Trotskyists from Labour party|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/23/unite-challenges-expulsion-of-alleged-trotskyists-from-labour-party|accessdate = 25 October 2015|work = The Guardian|date = 24 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-WorriedMPs\"/> However, Momentum was mired by the joining of members of these groups and the disruption they caused in the democratisation and organisation of Momentum.<ref name=\"NS-Corbynplzintervene\"/><ref name=\"GU-Lansmanvows2016\"/><ref name=\"BBC-Mmtmcivilwar2017\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fisher|first1=Lucy|last2=Savage|first2=Michael|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hard-left-corbynites-dismissed-as-softies-rbbhsqdqt|title=Hard-left Corbynites dismissed as softies|work=The Times|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref> An example was Jill Mountford, a long established member of AWL who was accused of bullying with Momentum.<ref name=\"Cowburn110117\">{{cite news |last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-affiliated-labour-party-jeremy-corbyn-members-must-join-a7520626.html|title=Momentum pushes activists to join Labour party to retain membership under new constitution|work=The Independent|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref> There was some consideration in these groups to disband and support Momentum- such as Left Unity in 2015 members proposed a motion to merge with Momentum several times, to no success.<ref>{{cite web|title = Left Unity party to consider joining Labour|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/19/left-unity-party-ken-loach-to-consider-joining-labour-jeremy-corbyn|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 6 December 2015|first = Patrick Wintour Political|last = editor}}</ref>\n\nThe movement has drawn comparisons to [[Militant (Trotskyist group)|the Militant Tendency]], or Militant, a group that was expelled by Labour under [[Neil Kinnock]] in the 1980s. Labour MP [[Owen Smith]] accused Momentum of using the same tactics as Militant such as threatening to deselect Labour MPs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2016/09/owen-smith-evokes-1980s-struggle-as-he-brands-momentum-a-party-within-a-party/|title=Owen Smith evokes 1980s struggle as he brands Momentum \"a party within a party\" |work= [[Labour List]] |date=16 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref> These concerns were echoed by former [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|deputy Labour leader]] Roy Hattersley.<ref name=\"Ob-Subversion\">{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/dec/02/labour-faces-subversion-momentum-far-left-roy-hattersley-watford-byelection |title= Labour faces subversion by Momentum and far left, says Roy Hattersley |author= Toby Helm and Michael Savage |work= [[The Observer]] |publisher= [[The Guardian]] |date= 2 December 2017 |accessdate= 20 March 2019}}</ref> [[Oliver Kamm]] of ''[[The Times]]'' wrote in October 2015: \"Like the Trotskyists of a generation ago Momentum is an [[entryism|entrist]] organisation that's parasitic on the Labour host. This time, though, the far left has managed to gain control of the party structures and is intent on making life tough for Labour MPs\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kamm |first=Oliver |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/thunderer/article4584025.ece |title=The real Labour party must refuse to work with Corbyn |work=The Times|location=London|date=13 October 2015|accessdate=26 July 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref> A Labour councillor in Liverpool in 2019 had commented about the presence of Momentum in the city by saying: \"I think Momentum in Liverpool is a mask for Militant. There are decent Momentum people and then there are the others who have their own agenda\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/feb/23/liverpool-wavertree-labour-constituency-antisemitism-luciana-berger-derek-hatton |title= Anger, denial and prejudice fester on the streets of Liverpool Wavertree |author= Andrew Anthony |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 23 February 2019 |accessdate= 28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nMomentum itself and a number of political commentators characterise their supposed relationship with other groups as unfair.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/is-momentum-a-return-to-the-old-days-of-labour-s-militant-tendency-a6782621.html|title=Is Momentum a return to the old days of Labour\u2019s militant tendency?|date=22 December 2015|publisher=}}</ref> In October 2015, Momentum stated would resist such entryism.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2015/10/pro-corbyn-group-momentum-vows-resist-swp-infiltration|title=Pro-Corbyn group Momentum vows to resist SWP \"infiltration\"|date=16 October 2015|author=George Eaton|author-link=George Eaton (journalist)|magazine=New Statesman}}</ref><ref name=\"HP-Schneider2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/10/20/momentum-labour-jeremy-corbyn-deselection_n_8337282.html |title=Momentum Is Not A 'Shadowy' Group With A 'Hit List' Of Labour MPs, Says Leading Organiser |publisher=[[Huffington Post]] |accessdate= 9 April 2020}}</ref> Author and journalist [[Michael Crick]] opposes the comparison to Militant, stating that \"the rise of Jeremy Corbyn can be attributed more to the phenomenon of '[[Corbynmania]]' than to hard-left entrism\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Crick|first1=Michael|title=Militant|date=10 March 2016|publisher=Biteback Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-1-78590-029-7}} (back cover)</ref> Former Labour MP [[Peter Kilfoyle]], who had acted as enforcer for the Labour leadership against Militant on Merseyside in the 1980s as the party's North West Regional Organiser, also rejected the comparison, instead describing Momentum as fulfilling the same kind of role on the left of the party as [[Progress (organisation)|Progress]] did on the right.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/membership/2016/aug/05/peter-kilfoyle-liverpool-labour-momentum-jeremy-corbyn |title=Peter Kilfoyle: 'Something is going wrong in Liverpool' |last=MacAskill |first=Ewen|author-link=Ewen MacAskill |date=5 August 2016 |website=[[theguardian.com]]|access-date=28 July 2018}}</ref> In December 2015, Labour's then deputy leader [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] made a cynical commentary on the ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme about the group: \"They look like a bit of a rabble to me, but I don't think they are a problem for the Labour Party\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Watt|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/dec/04/labour-split-exposed-tom-watson-momentum-rabble-livingstone|title=Labour split exposed as Tom Watson describes Momentum as a 'rabble'|work=The Guardian|date=4 December 2015|accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref> Schneider commented in response to this accusation as such: \"The purpose of Momentum is not to have internal factional battles, it's to look outside\".<ref name=\"TG2015deslect\">{{cite news|last1=Gilligan|first1=Andrew|title=The Corbyn hardcore plotting to deselect Labour moderates|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11981745/The-Corbyn-hardcore-plotting-to-deselect-Labour-moderates.html|accessdate=23 November 2015|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== International relationships ===\nMomentum has built ties with other political organisations across North America and Europe. They have collaborated with the Canadian [[Leap Manifesto|Leap movement]], the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]]'s [[Young Socialists in the SPD|Young Socialists]],<ref name=\"SPD activist want Momentum\">{{cite news |title=SPD activists seek help of Momentum to dash German coalition deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/24/germany-spd-social-democratic-party-coalition-deal-momentum-cdu |newspaper=The Guardian |author= Philip Oltermann |date= 24 January 2018 |access-date= 28 July 2018}}</ref> the [[Democratic Socialists of America]]<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/26/momentum-plan-tap-into-new-us-socialism-labour-conference |title= How Momentum is tapping into the new US socialism |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 26 September 2018 |accessdate= 9 November 2018}}</ref> and similar organisations in Greece. In 2018, Rees and Klug went on a ten-week lecture tour of the United States to educate progressive activists and members of the [[National Nurses United]] union on political campaigning techniques as well as advising Real Justice.<ref name=\"Sights on Donald Trump\">{{cite web |title=Exclusive: Momentum founders turn their sights on Donald Trump |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/momentum-founders-turn-their-sights-on-donald-trump/ |publisher=[[i (newspaper)|i]] |author= Nigel Morris |date= 27 July 2018 |access-date= 28 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Campaigning history ==\n=== Early formation ===\nMomentum undertook a campaign called Democracy SOS to address the problem of the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Conservative-Liberal Democrat government]] implementing the changes to the electoral register to an [[Individual Electoral Registration]] system. The Electoral Commission recommended that the program be implemented a year later than it was. The EC believed, based on 2015 records, that there were eight million people eligible for registration but not registered and 1.9 million people previously registered who have been dropped off by the changes. Momentum utilized their network to campaign in towns and university campuses to encourage people to register.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyns-momentum-activist-network-announces-mass-voter-registration-campaign-a6698691.html |title=Jeremy Corbyn's Momentum activist network announces mass voter registration campaign|author=Jon Stone|date=19 October 2015|work=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://democracy-sos.peoplesmomentum.com/|title=Democracy SOS \u2013 Momentum|publisher=Democracy SOS}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.opendemocracy.net/uk/alison-whyte/democracy-sos-stop-electoral-register-cull |title= Democracy SOS - stop the electoral register cull |author= Alison Whyte |publisher= [[Open Democracy]] |date= 23 October 2015 |accessdate= 17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Labour's former shadow chancellor [[John McDonnell]] praise Momentum for their work in the [[2016 United Kingdom local elections|local elections that May]]. They coordinated activists from Brighton and London to areas like [[Hastings]], [[Crawley]] and [[Harlow]]; activists in the [[North West England|North West]] were directed to [[West Lancashire]].<ref name=\"Indy-JohnthankMomentum\">{{cite news |last= Stone |first= Jon |date= 10 May 2016 |title= John McDonnell says Momentum activists helped drive Labour\u2019s better-than-expected election result |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-says-left-wing-momentum-activists-drove-labour-s-better-than-expected-election-result-a7022816.html |work= The Independent |access-date= 11 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nAfter the [[2017 Stoke-on-Trent Central by-election|Stoke-on-Trent Central]] and [[2017 Copeland by-election|Copeland by-elections]] were called, Momentum mobilised its large activist base to campaign for both. Momentum launched two pieces of technology to help this, a Phone Banking web application called Grassroots Now (previously used in Corbyn's Labour leadership election campaigns in 2015 and 2016) and a carpooling web application to help activists travel to the campaign days from across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peoplesmomentum.com/by_elections|title=By-elections|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2017/02/momentum-carpool-brings-activists-to-crucial-by-election-campaigns|title=Momentum carpool brings activists to crucial by-election campaigns - LabourList|date=10 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2017/01/momentum-seeks-to-move-on-from-internal-fueds-and-help-deliver-by-election-victories|title=Momentum seeks to move on from feuds and help deliver by-election victories - LabourList|date=26 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Ultimately, Labour Party candidate in Stoke-on-trent Gareth Snell won while in the traditional Labour stronghold of Copeland the Labour candidate Gillian Troughton lost to her Conservative opponent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39064149|title=Tories in historic by-election Copeland win|date=24 February 2017|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 general election campaign ===\n{{main|2017 United Kingdom general election}}\nIn the run-up to the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|general election on 8 June 2017]], Momentum worked to mobilise voters and encourage volunteers to canvass on behalf of Labour. Their campaign strategy was to target marginal seats rather than defend safe seats.<ref name=\"Vice-secretweapon\"/><ref name=\"Jacobin-makeCorbynPM2019\"/> As part of this ambition the group created 'MyNearestMarginal.com', a website which allows voters to search for campaigning events in marginal constituencies closest to them;<ref name=\"WiredMCM2019\"/> and ElectionDayPledge.com, where voters can pledge to volunteer on Polling Day, were created. Momentum also worked with organisers from [[Bernie Sanders]]' [[Bernie Sanders 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]] to hold training sessions for volunteers, such as persuasive conversation training.<ref name=\"GUberniecampaign\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/30/the-us-sanders-campaigners-lending-corybn-hand-bernie-momentum|title=The US Bernie Sanders campaigners lending Jeremy Corbyn a hand|last=Khomami|first=Nadia|date=20 May 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=30 May 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/> It drafted in senior figures from Sanders' campaign, including Erika Uyterhoeven, formerly a national director for outer-state organising,<ref name=\"independent1\">{{cite news |last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-what-happens-jeremy-corbyn-post-general-election-2017-labour-defeat-hard-left-wing-a7777506.html|title=Momentum: What happens to the Jeremy Corbyn-backing organisation after the general election?|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref> Grayson Lookner, Jeremy Parkin and Kim McMurray.<ref name=\"theweek\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/general-election-2017/85501/how-momentum-helped-sway-the-general-election|title=How Momentum helped sway the general election|magazine=[[The Week]]|date=12 June 2017|accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThey had an effective social media presence with many of their low-budget videos becoming virally spread. One example was \"Daddy, do you hate me?\", which was watched by 12.7 million unique Facebook users- at the time more than one in three in the UK.<ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/> By the end of the election campaign, Momentum reached 51 million views on all of their videos.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/>\n\nMembership of the organisation increased by 1,500 within four days of the general election<ref name=\"theguardian2\"/> and by another 3,000 within two months.<ref name=\"newstatesman1\">{{cite magazine |last1=Murugesu|first1=Jason|last2=Varghese|first2=Sanjana|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/2017/08/how-momentum-activists-are-learning-win-over-tory-voters|title=How Momentum activists are learning to win over Tory voters|magazine=[[New Statesman]]|date=15 August 2017|accessdate=15 August 2017}}</ref> The organisation's [[Facebook]] page reached 23.7 million views and videos were watched by 12.7 million unique users. In total, Momentum spent less than \u00a32,000 advertising on the social media platform.<ref name=\"independent1\"/> In May 2017, [[Noam Chomsky]] claimed the future of the party must lie with the left of the party and Momentum, saying: \"The constituency of the Labour Party, the new participants, the Momentum group and so on, [...] if there is to be a serious future for the Labour Party that is where it is in my opinion\".<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite news |last=Asthana|first=Anushka|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/10/labour-partys-future-lies-with-momentum-says-noam-chomsky|title=Labour party's future lies with Momentum, says Noam Chomsky|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 May 2017|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> On polling day, 10,000 Momentum activists knocked on an estimated 1.2 million doors in the UK.<ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/>\n\nThe general election led to Labour losing five seats to the Conservatives, but Labour won 28 from them, as well as six from the SNP and two from the Lib Dems.  Almost every constituency that Momentum targeted was gained by Labour.<ref name=\"WiredMCM2019\"/> After the general election, Giles Kenningham, former Conservative Party director of communications, said in July 2017: \"Labour have used Momentum to devastating effect\".<ref name=\"ft-devestating\">{{cite news |last=Bond|first=David|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d1c854f0-4cea-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43|title=Labour\u2019s slick online campaign outguns Tory press|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> Later in the month, [[Michael Gove]], Conservative MP said: \"The Conservative Party can learn a lot from Momentum\".<ref name=\"inews\">{{cite news |last=Landin|first=Conrad|url=https://www.inews.co.uk/essentials/news/politics/michael-gove-conservatives-can-learn-lot-momentum/|title=Labour\u2019s slick online campaign outguns Tory press|work= |location= |publisher=[[i (newspaper)|i]]|date=25 June 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> In August, it was announced that the [[Communication Workers Union (UK)|Communications Workers Union]] will formally affiliate to Momentum after its ruling executive voted unanimously in favour to join the organisation.<ref name=\"newstatesman2\">{{cite magazine|last=Bush|first=Stephen|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2017/08/britains-largest-communications-union-affiliate-momentum|title=Britain's largest communications union to affiliate to Momentum|magazine=[[New Statesman]]|date=23 August 2017|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref> A former critic of the Labour left and Corbyn, [[John McTernan]], joined Momentum in summer 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mairs|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/88199/watch-arch-blairite-john-mcternan-joins-momentum|title=WATCH: Arch-Blairite John McTernan joins Momentum|publisher=Politics Home|date=13 August 2017|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref> In summer 2017, Adam Klug resigned as national co-ordinator following the snap general election. In October 2017, Emma Rees, a co-founder of the group, stood down as national co-ordinator. Laura Parker who left her role as Jeremy Corbyn's political secretary before the national conference replaced Rees as national co-ordinator.<ref name=\"labourlist1\">{{cite news |last=Edwards|first=Peter|url=https://www.labourlist.org/2017/10/exclusive-new-shake-up-at-momentum-as-two-top-organisers-resign/|title=Momentum membership soars above 30,000 as Corbyn-supporting Labour group's influence grows|work= |location= |publisher=Labour List|date=24 October 2017|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] (EC) announced that Momentum had been fined \u00a316,700 for multiple breaches of electoral law, including failing to accurately report donations during the general election period.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=6 March 2019 |title=Momentum fined by Electoral Commission for multiple breaches of electoral law |publisher= |url=https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/i-am-a/journalist/electoral-commission-media-centre/party-and-election-finance-to-keep/momentum-fined-by-electoral-commission-for-multiple-breaches-of-electoral-law |website=electoralcommission.org.uk |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> The fine for not submitting an accurate spending return was the biggest issued to a non-party campaign.<ref name=\"BBCECruling2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47468571|title=Momentum fined over election spending|work=[[BBC News]]|date=2019-03-06|access-date=2019-03-06|language=en-GB}}</ref> Though the group was initially investigated by the EC with the concern that they had overspent, the EC found this was not the case.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-fined-electoral-commission-law-corbyn-labour-a8809666.html |title= Momentum fined more than \u00a316,000 for multiple breaches of electoral law during 2017 election |author= Ashley Cowburn |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 6 March 2019 |accessdate= 14 March 2019}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=April 2019}} Momentum's then national treasurer Puru Miah, a councilor in [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets|Tower Hamlets]], commented \"we have put in place comprehensive systems so we can fully adhere to regulations\".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.eastlondonadvertiser.co.uk/news/politics/cllr-puru-miah-admits-momentum-s-election-offences-1-5927212 |title= Tower Hamlets councilor holds his hands up to Momentum\u2019s election offences over cash payments as its treasurer |author= Mike Brooke |publisher= [[East London Advertiser]] |date= 8 March 2019 |accessdate= 20 March 2019}}</ref> In April 2020 Momentum published a report disecting their performance in both the 2017 and 19 general elections- saying that constituencies such as [[Broxtowe (UK Parliament constituency)|Broxtowe]], [[Hendon (UK Parliament constituency)|Hendon]], [[Morley and Outwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Morley and Outwood]], [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]], [[Pudsey (UK Parliament constituency)|Pudsey]], [[Thurrock (UK Parliament constituency)|Thurrock]] and [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]] could have been won with the enhanced ground support they had reached by 2019.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/>\n\n=== The Unseat! campaign and expansion into local government (2017\u20132019) ===\nIn aftermath of the 2017 general election, Momentum mobilised the Unseat campaign with prominent partners such as [[Owen Jones (writer)|Owen Jones]], targeting constituencies where prominent Conservative MPs have a small majority and could be susceptible to a Labour win at the next general election. Thousands have attended Unseat events in seats held by then Education Secretary [[Justine Greening]] ([[Putney (UK Parliament constituency)|Putney]]), former DWP Secretary [[Iain Duncan Smith]] ([[Chingford and Woodford Green (UK Parliament constituency)|Chingford and Woodford Green]]) and current Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] ([[Uxbridge and South Ruislip (UK Parliament constituency)|Uxbridge and South Ruislip]]).<ref>{{cite web|url= https://labourlist.org/2018/05/owen-jones-momentum-campaigning-was-crucial-to-labours-local-election-gains/ |title= Owen Jones: Momentum campaigning was crucial to Labour\u2019s local election gains |author= [[Owen Jones (writer)|Owen Jones]] |publisher= [[Labour List]] |date= 8 May 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/08/03/unseatboris-momentum-sets-training-camps-get-rid-foreign-secretary/ |title= #UnseatBoris: Momentum sets up training camps to get rid of the Foreign Secretary |author= Helena Horton |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date= 3 August 2017 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://leftfootforward.org/2017/08/revealed-the-eight-tories-momentum-are-now-gearing-up-to-unseat/ |title= Revealed: The eight Tories Momentum are now gearing up to unseat |author= Josiah Mortimer |publisher= [[Left Foot Forward]] |date= 16 August 2017 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/2018/08/chingford-corbynite-faiza-shaheen-her-mission-oust-iain-duncan-smith |title= The Chingford Corbynite: Faiza Shaheen on her mission to oust Iain Duncan Smith |author= George Eaton|author-link=George Eaton (journalist)|magazine= [[New Statesman]] |date= 8 August 2018 |accessdate= 27 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/news/labour-and-momentum-rally-to-target-paul-maynard-s-marginal-seat-1-9282395 |title= Labour and Momentum rally to target Paul Maynard's marginal seat |author= James Graves|newspaper= [[Blackpool Gazette]] |date= 2 August 2018 |accessdate= 27 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.swindonadvertiser.co.uk/news/16161361.activists-aim-to-unseat-the-tories-in-may/ |title= Owen Jones and Momentum descend on Swindon to \u2018unseat Tory council\u2019 |author= Thomas Haworth |publisher= [[Swindon Advisor]] |date= 16 April 2018 |accessdate= 27 February 2019}}</ref> The campaign motivated Duncan Smith to contact local Conservative associations to organise activists to run counter campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/alexspence/these-leaked-whatsapp-chats-show-iain-duncan-smiths-pleas |title= These Leaked WhatsApp Chats Show Iain Duncan Smith\u2019s Pleas For Help After His Seat Was Targeted By Momentum |author= Alex Spence |publisher= [[Buzzfeed News]] |date= 20 March 2018 |accessdate= 27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nBecause the Labour Party believed another [[Next United Kingdom general election|snap general election]] was likely, the party ran the selection procedure to have a slate of parliamentary candidates in place for the 96 marginal constituencies- Momentum backed several candidates.<ref name=\"GU2018marginals\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/19/momentum-backed-labour-candidates-to-contest-most-marginal-seats |title= Momentum-backed Labour candidates to contest most-marginal seats |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 19 March 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019 }}</ref> By January 2019, it was recorded that over half of their 67 selections were successful in becoming candidates.<ref name=\"GU2019marginals\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/05/unite-momentum-dominate-labour-selections-candidates-key-marginals |title= Unite and Momentum candidates dominate Labour\u2019s selection races |author= Eleni Courea |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 5 January 2019 |accessdate= 25 February 2019 }}</ref> Additionally, Momentum wished to influence the new manifesto by promising to introduce a four-day working week and a [[Green New Deal]]- an idea of mass state investment to address climate change.<ref name=\"GU-Radicalmomentum\"/>\n\nMomentum established a candidate network in which they provide support to new councillors, encourage women to stand, give them spaces to discuss policy and also training on the success of Labour controlled councils like [[Salford City Council|Salford]] and [[Preston City Council|Preston]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/feb/06/momentum-network-trains-councillors-to-fight-local-elections |title= Momentum sets up councillor network to target local elections |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 6 February 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> Notable Momentum-backed selections from the [[2018 United Kingdom local elections|2018 local elections]] was [[Rokhsana Fiaz]] for [[Mayor of Newham]], who successfully became mayor on an increased majority.<ref name=\"GU2018marginals\"/> Trafford Labour party's leader cited Momentum as a key reason for why Labour gained seats in borough.<ref name=\"LFF-2018LE\">{{cite web|url= https://leftfootforward.org/2018/05/no-momentum-didnt-cost-labour-victory-last-night/ |title= No, Momentum didn\u2019t cost Labour a victory in the local elections |author= Josiah Mortimer |publisher= [[Left Foot Forward]] |date= 4 May 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> A Momentum-supported councillor Joseph Ejiofor became the leader of [[Haringey London Borough Council]] after the elections in London.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/momentum-leader-takes-over-haringey-labour-council-despite-party-vote-a3834431.html |title= Momentum leader takes over Haringey Labour council despite party vote |author= Kate Proctor |newspaper= [[London Evening Standard]] |date= 9 May 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, following the resignation of 9 Labour members of parliament, with 8 becoming members of the [[centrism|centrist]] [[The Independent Group|Independent Group]] with resigning Conservatives,<ref name=GU-TIG>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/02/rebel-labour-mps-set-to-quit-party-and-form-centre-group|title=Rebel Labour MPs set to quit party and form centre group|last=Helm|first=Toby|date=18 February 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=18 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218134948/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/02/rebel-labour-mps-set-to-quit-party-and-form-centre-group|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Momentum began to organise resources and activists to campaign in these seats. They wished to initiate public pressure from their constituents to trigger by-elections. The group raised \u00a315,000 from their activists in the hours after their split to contribute to funding this campaign.<ref name=\"ind-byelectionsnow\">{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-split-momentum-campaign-resignations-corbyn-independent-group-a8790121.html |title= Momentum launches campaigning drive against ex-Labour MPs who have joined Independent Group\n|author= Ashley Cowburn |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 22 February 2019 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> On 19 March, the group organized 100 activists in [[Streatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Streatham]], [[Chuka Umunna]]'s constituency, with Owen Jones, [[Diane Abbott]] and [[Ash Sarkar]] speaking to the activists at a rally.<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/elections/2019/03/momentum-has-begun-campaigning-unseat-tig-mps |title= Momentum has begun campaigning to unseat TIG MPs |author= Eleni Courea |magazine= [[New Statesman]] |date= 19 March 2019 |accessdate= 20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 United Kingdom local elections|2019 local elections]], James Driscoll was selected as Labour candidate for the inaugural  [[2019 North of Tyne mayoral election|first North of Tyne mayoral election]] became a notable Momentum-backed selection.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/jamie-driscoll-north-tyne-mayor-15860074 |title= Who is Jamie Driscoll? Labour's left-wing North of Tyne mayoral candidate |author= Sean Seddon |publisher= [[The Chronicle and the Journal]] |date= 21 February 2019 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> Driscoll won this election with 56.1% of the vote in the second round. In addition, [[Brighton and Hove City Council]], where Momentum backed 12 Labour candidates<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/19/brighton-well-organised-momentum-group-shifts-focus-to-local-elections |title= Brighton: well-organised Momentum group shifts focus to local elections |author= Dan Sabbagh |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 19 March 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> and [[Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council|Sandwell council]] were key focals point for Momentum.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Madeley |first1=Pete |title='Completely anti-democratic': Tom Watson slams 'hard-left takeover' of Sandwell Council |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/politics/2019/04/02/tom-watson-hits-out-at-hard-left-takeover-of-sandwell-councils-labour-group/ |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=[[The Express and Star]] |date=2 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2019 general election campaign===\n{{main|2019 United Kingdom general election}}\nFollowing the announcement of the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|12 December 2019 snap general election]], Momentum called for a large mobilisation of Momentum and Labour members.<ref name=\"LL-largecall\">{{cite web |last1=Rodgers |first1=Sienna |title=Momentum hosts \"largest mobilising call in UK political history\" with Corbyn |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/10/momentum-hosts-largest-mobilising-call-in-uk-political-history-with-corbyn/ |website=[[LabourList]] |accessdate=4 November 2019 |date=30 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\">{{cite news |last1=Eaton |first1=George |authorlink1=George Eaton |title=Inside Momentum: \"We\u2019re going to be here long after Jeremy Corbyn and I are dead\" |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/12/inside-momentum-we-re-going-be-here-long-after-jeremy-corbyn-and-i-are-dead |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=[[New Statesman]] |date=4 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The group increased their number of paid staff from 13 to 56 for the election campaign period.<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/> The group set a funding target of \u00a350,000 in 48 hours, however exceeded this and raised \u00a3100,000 in 12 hours.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peat |first1=Jack |title=Momentum raises \u00a3100,000 in 12 hours as it gears up for snap election |url=https://www.thelondoneconomic.com/politics/momentum-raises-100000-in-12-hours-as-it-gears-up-for-snap-election/30/10/ |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=[[The London Economic]] |date=30 October 2019}}</ref> Within six days of this funding drive Momentum have raised \u00a3255,000 from 10,000 individual donations, averaging at \u00a326 per donation which came close to beating the amount raised during the entirety of the 2017 General election campaign.<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\">{{cite news |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |title=Momentum seeks 'Labour legends' to take a week off to campaign |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/04/labours-momentum-raises-250000-in-six-days-to-fight-election |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 November 2019}}</ref> Within 10 days, the group reached over \u00a3300,000 from 11,000 donations. Parker commented on these funds saying the organisation will be able to \"scale up every aspect of our operation from the get-go, which will allow us to deliver a campaign like nothing this country has ever seen before.\u201d<ref name=\"I-300k\">{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=Nigel |title=Momentum raises \u00a3300,000 for election campaign, dwarfing funds last time round |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/general-election-2019-momentum-jeremy-corbyn-labour-party-919594 |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=[[i (newspaper)|i]] |language=en}}</ref>\n\nMomentum created different tools and initiatives to help activists to organise. Prior to the campaign in September Momentum created a website \"Univotes\" to help students strategically plan which constituency is better for them to vote in; as students can register at both their home address and student address. The student vote been cited by Momentum as why Labour won in [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]], [[Warwick and Leamington (UK Parliament constituency)|Warwick and Leamington]], [[Portsmouth South (UK Parliament constituency)|Portsmouth South]], [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]] and [[Lincoln (UK Parliament constituency)|Lincoln]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lo |first1=Joe |title=Vote at home or at uni? Momentum launches tool for students to decide |url=https://leftfootforward.org/2019/09/vote-at-home-or-at-uni-momentum-launches-tool-for-students-to-decide/ |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=[[Left Foot Forward]] |date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |title=Momentum launches digital tool to help students register to vote |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/13/momentum-launches-digital-tool-to-help-students-register-to-vote |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=12 September 2019}}</ref> They created a website \"mycampaignmap.com\"- as a successor the to the 'My Nearest Marginal' website used for the 2017 election- which helps activists to coordinate their efforts in areas they are most needed.<ref name=\"LL-largecall\"/> My Campaign Map was used to organise over 21,000 events for the election period,<ref name=\"WiredMCM2019\">{{cite web |last1=Clarke |first1=Laurie |title=Inside Momentum's data-driven march to put Corbyn in Number 10 |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/momentum-labour-party-my-campaign-map |publisher=[[Wired UK]] |accessdate=4 December 2019 |date=30 November 2019}}</ref> and had over 170,000 unique visitors.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/>\n\nMomentum created a new type of volunteers called \"Labour Legends\", who took time off from work and commit at least a full week of campaigning in their area, or to volunteer in other constituencies.<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\"/> In 10 days this initiative acquired over 1,000 people have signed up, providing 40,000 volunteer hours,<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\">{{cite news |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |title=Momentum scales up for 'once-in-a-generation chance' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/19/momentum-scales-up-for-once-in-a-generation-chance |accessdate=25 November 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=19 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Vice-secretweapon\">{{cite news |title=Inside Momentum, Labour's Secret Weapon |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/a35me4/momentum-corbyn-labour-election-2019 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |author= Ruby Lott-Lavigna |work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |date=18 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and eventually rising to over 1,400 people getting involved,<ref name=\"WiredMCM2019\"/><ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/> 500 of which were allocated to marginal seats.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/> Momentum additionally encourages Labour party members abroad in Europe, The United States and Australia to register British expats to vote and to participate in phone banking from where they live.<ref name=\"GU-DSAsupport\">{{cite web |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |title=Labour gets support from Bernie Sanders campaigners in US |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/26/labour-gets-support-from-bernie-sanders-campaigners-in-us |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=4 December 2019 |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe group developed their campaign strategy with three principles in mind, according to Emma Rees: people power, the targeting of marginal seats, and the idea of getting everybody to step up. This was done by following a [[Decentralization|decentralised model]] in which activists have both a clear understanding of the aims and taking on organisational roles.<ref name=\"Jacobin-makeCorbynPM2019\">{{cite news |last1=Doherty |first1=Alex |title=Momentum Activists Are Trying to Make Jeremy Corbyn Prime Minister |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2019/11/momentum-labour-party-emma-rees-election |date=13 November 2019 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |work=[[Jacobin (magazine)|Jacobin]]}}</ref> Momentum has created several opportunities for activists to get involved in other ways of promotion- these include \u201cLet\u2019s Go\u201d teams who communicate on do phone banking using [[Whatsapp]], volunteers who watch through interviews of Conservative and Liberal Democrat politicians to be used for videos<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/> and also people creating videos of themselves explaining why they are voting labour and posting them on social media to help engage with voters on all available platforms.<ref name=\"I-300k\"/>\n\nMomentum used social media advertising to encourage people to register to vote for the election. One of their adverts targeted [[Urdu]] speakers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volpicelli |first1=Gian |title=The Facebook election fight is now between the Tories and Momentum |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/facebook-adverts-general-election-momentum |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=[[Wired UK]] |date=29 November 2019}}</ref> The organising group controversially made a video for twitter based on a [[Coca-Cola]] Christmas advert that circulates every year. They were asked to cease and desist by the Coca-Cola company and the advertisement was taken down.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tidy |first1=Joe |title=Row over Labour group's use of famous Coca-Cola ad |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50520783 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=22 November 2019}}</ref> By the end of the election, their videos had a combined viewing of 106 million, double that of the last election.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/>\n\nIn 2020, Momentum submitted a report to the Labour party's \"Labour Together Review\", which was a cross-factional analysis of the party's performance and strategy, making several recommendations on the tools and approach for future elections.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\">{{cite web |title=Momentum Submission to the Labour Together Review of the 2019 General Election |url=https://peoplesmomentum.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Momentums-Labour-Together-Submission.pdf |publisher=Momentum |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Labour leadership elections and recent campaigning ===\nFollowing defeat in the 2019 general election in which Labour lost 60 seats, Jeremy Corbyn and Momentum's national coordinator Laura Parker resigned.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/22/insults-infighting-battle-lines-drawn-future-labour-party|title= Labour: anger, recrimination and bitterness mark fresh battle for party\u2019s soul |last= Helm|first= Tom |publisher= [[The Guardian]] |date= 22 December 2019 |accessdate= 12 January 2020}}</ref> Corbyn's triggered a [[2020 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|leadership election]], which was coupled with the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|deputy leadership election]], with the results to be unveiled for both in April 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Who will be Labour's next leader? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50781341 |accessdate=16 December 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Rowena |last2=Pidd |first2=Helen |title=Labour leadership race begins as senior figures back Rebecca Long-Bailey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/15/labour-leadership-race-begins-as-senior-figures-back-rebecca-long-bailey |accessdate=16 December 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=15 December 2019}}</ref> On 14 January Momentum ran a 2 day online consultation with their members whether to endorse [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] for leader and [[Angela Rayner]] for deputy leader. The closed format of the consultation was controversial.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cowburn |first1=Ashley |title=Momentum faces backlash over \u2018ludicrous\u2019 Labour leadership ballot of members |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-leadership-momentum-member-ballot-deputy-candidates-a9283826.html |publisher=[[The Independent]] |language=en |date=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bartlett |first1=Nicola |title=Momentum slammed for only giving members one option on Labour leadership ballot |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/backlash-after-momentum-sends-members-21283993 |accessdate=16 January 2020 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=15 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> 7,395 members participated with 70% supporting Long-Bailey and 52% supporting Rayner.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chappell |first1=Elliot |title=Momentum back Long-Bailey and Rayner after member ballot |url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/momentum-backs-long-bailey-and-rayner-after-members-ballot/ |publisher=[[LabourList]] |accessdate=17 January 2020 |date=16 January 2020}}</ref> Momentum planned hundreds of phone banking events to support Long-Bailey.<ref>{{cite news |last1=editor |first1=Rowena Mason Deputy political |title=Labour must stir up democratic revolution to win power, says Long-Bailey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/16/labour-must-stir-up-democratic-revolution-to-win-power-says-long-bailey |accessdate=17 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 January 2020}}</ref> Keir Starmer won the election in the first round - with Long-Bailey wining 28% of the vote - and Momentum failed to win any of the NEC by elections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52164589|title=Keir Starmer elected as new Labour leader|date=2020-04-04|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/apr/04/labour-leadership-election-winner-keir-starmer-long-bailey-nandy-and-jeremy-corbyns-successor-to-be-announced-at-1045am-live-news|title=Keir Starmer elected Labour leader with 56% of vote on first round \u2014 as it happened|date=2020-04-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In response to his victory, Momentum congratulated him and positioned themselves as challenging and working with the new leadership to push for 'transformational policies'.<ref name=\"PH-Keirwon\">{{cite news |last1=Schofield |first1=Kevin |title=Momentum vows to 'hold Keir Starmer to account' after Labour left suffers heavy defeats |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/momentum-vows-to-hold-keir-starmer-to-account-after-labour-left-suffers-heavy-defeats |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=[[PoliticsHome]] |date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nLeading to the [[2020 United Kingdom local elections|2020 local elections]], the [[London Labour Party]] changed its selection process for [[London Assembly#Assembly members|assembly members]] so that party members select new candidates. Four assembly members were standing down leading up to the election. This was believed to be an opportunity for Momentum, who have gained influence in the regional party in 2018 regional conference elections,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://labourlist.org/2019/03/labour-left-sweeps-the-london-regional-board/ |title= Labour left sweeps the London regional board |author= Sienna Rodgers |publisher= [[LabourList]] |date= 3 March 2019 |accessdate= 19 March 2019}}</ref> to put up candidates so they can push [[Sadiq Khan]]'s election manifesto to the left.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/05/labour-london-aembly-members-face-reselection-fight |title= Labour London assembly members face reselection fight |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 5 November 2018 |accessdate= 5 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/momentum-bids-to-push-sadiq-khan-manifesto-to-left-a4092731.html |title= Momentum bids to push Sadiq Khan manifesto to Left |author= Sophia Sleigh |newspaper= [[London Evening Standard]] |date= 16 March 2019 |accessdate= 17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Issues and other campaigning ==\n=== Austerity ===\nOne of Momentum's primary objectives was to create an anti-austerity movement in the UK connected to the Labour Party.<ref name=\"BBC-Mmtmcivilwar2017\"/> In particular, Momentum criticised Osborne's proposal to cut [[tax credit]] payments for working families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noworkpenalty.peoplesmomentum.com/|title=No Work Penalty|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/a-b59a-Momentums-potential-to-unify-and-energise-political-campaigning|title=Momentum\u2019s potential to unify and energise political campaigning|author=Steve Sweeney|newspaper=Morning Star|date=24 October 2015|accessdate=3 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, local Momentum groups started to collect and volunteer for food banks.<ref name=\"theguardian2\"/>\n\n=== Syria bombing ===\nMomentum called for its membership to lobby Labour MPs \"to support Corbyn, not Cameron, over Syria\" on [[Twitter]], linking to the [[Stop the War Coalition]]'s Don't Bomb Syria campaign which opposed the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government's proposal to extend its bombing sorties against [[Daesh]] (also known as ISIS) from Daesh-held territory in Iraq to also cover Daesh-held territory in Syria. Corbyn had argued that Cameron's government lacked a credible plan for defeating Daesh and that the bombing in Syria would not increase the United Kingdom's national security. Corbyn has also stated his view that military action should always be a last resort. Some Labour MPs criticised Momentum's move to lobby on party political grounds before the Labour party's official position on military action had been decided, with [[Gavin Shuker]] asking: \"Who decided this was your position on Syria, and to lobby MPs in this way?\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dathan|first1=Matt|title=Jeremy Corbyn campaign group urges Labour MPs to reject air strikes in Syria|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-campaign-group-urges-labour-mps-to-reject-air-strikes-in-syria-a6745141.html|accessdate=23 November 2015|newspaper=Independent|date=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Bankrupt Climate Change ===\nIn March 2019, Momentum started a campaign called Bankrupt Climate Change, a direct action campaign protesting outside of [[Barclays]]' banks in 40 different local groups. The campaign's objective is to raise awareness for Barclays bank investing in fossil fuel companies.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/30/john-mcdonnell-backs-momentum-on-barclays-protest |title= John McDonnell backs Momentum on Barclays protest |author= Damien Gayle |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 30 March 2019 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/17530689.bradford-momentum-branch-to-stage-city-centre-climate-change-protest/ |title= Bradford Momentum branch to stage city centre climate change protest |author= Felicity Macnamara |publisher= [[Telegraph and Argus]] |date= 28 March 2019 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref> They reference a report says that Barclays as the largest financer in Europe and sixth in the world for financing the fossil fuel companies.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://bright-green.org/2019/03/21/momentum-members-joins-fight-against-barclays-fossil-fuel-funding/ |title= Momentum members join fight against Barclays\u2019 fossil fuel funding |author= Chris Saltmarsh |publisher= [[Bright Green]] |date= 21 March 2019 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Antisemitism allegations ===\nSince 2015, there have been a series of allegations of antisemitism against Labour Party members. Many leading figures in Momentum were Jewish or of Jewish heritage, such as  Klug,<ref name=\"JC-Momentumsojewish\"/> Lansman,<ref name=\"GU-Lansmanproblems2019\"/> Schneider,<ref name=\"JC-Momentumsojewish\"/> Rhea Wolfson<ref name=\"FT-insidethebeast\">{{cite news |last1=Judah |first1=Ben |title=Momentum: inside Labour\u2019s revolutionary movement |url=https://www.ft.com/content/0e99fc98-4872-11e8-8ae9-4b5ddcca99b3 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=27 April 2018}}</ref> and [[Jackie Walker (activist)|Jackie Walker]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mortimer|first=Caroline|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/anti-semitism-row-momentum-organiser-jackie-walker-readmitted-to-labour-party-following-racism-a7053966.html|title=Anti-Semitism row: Momentum organiser Jackie Walker readmitted to Labour party following racism allegations|work=[[The Independent]]|date=28 May 2016|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> Walker, Momentum's vice-chair, was expelled from the Labour Party for behaviour related to allegations of antisemitism.<ref>Jessica Elgot: [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/27/labour-expels-jackie-walker-for-leaked-antisemitism-comments ''Labour expels Jackie Walker for leaked antisemitism remarks'']. The Guardian, 27 March 2019</ref> In April 2018, Joshua Garfield, a Jewish youth officer in a Momentum branch in London, resigned from his role because, he says, antisemitism from members of the branch was making him feel \"sometimes unsafe and certainly untrusted\".<ref name=\"JC-Momentumsojewish\"/><ref>https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-momentum-organiser-resigns-over-deep-seated-prejudices-in-local-branch/</ref><ref>https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jewish-labour-party-momentum-antisemitism-joshua-garfield-newham-atrociously-offensive-1.462137</ref> Garfield was a member and later officer of the [[Jewish Labour Movement]] who appeared in the [[Panorama (TV programme)|Panorama]] programme on antisemitism in the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/joshua-garfield-selected-as-labour-s-candidate-against-tory-chairman-james-cleverley-1.490814|title=BBC Panorama whistleblower selected as Labour's candidate against Tory Chairman James Cleverley|date=29 October 2019|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nMomentum itself has also had issues with individual members<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-antisemitism-momentum-barnet-jews-jeremy-corbyn-israel-a8473501.html |title= Momentum activists accused of 'anti-Zionist ranting' in Labour antisemitism row |author= Benjamin Kentish |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 1 August 2018 |accessdate= 17 July 2019}}</ref> and have accepted that some Labour members have expressed antisemitism,<ref name=\"JC-Momentumsojewish\">{{cite news|url= https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/momentum-is-so-jewish-claims-leading-labour-activist-1.463274|title= Momentum \u2018is so Jewish\u2019 claims leading Labour activist |author= Lee Harpin |newspaper= [[The Jewish Chronicle]] |date= 30 April 2018 |accessdate= 17 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/antisemitism-labour-jeremy-corbyn-smears-momentum-a8285656.html |title= Antisemitism in Labour cannot be dismissed as smears, say Momentum |author= Andrew Woodcock |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 2 April 2018 |accessdate= 17 July 2019}}</ref> with Lansman attributing this to \"conspiracy theorists\" joining.<ref name=\"GU-Lansmanproblems2019\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/25/labour-has-widespread-problem-with-antisemitism-momentum-founder-jon-lansman |title= Labour has widespread problem with antisemitism \u2013 Momentum founder |author= Seth Jacobson |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 25 February 2019 |accessdate= 16 July 2019}}</ref> Such [[List of conspiracy theories#Antisemitic conspiracy theories|antisemitic conspiracy theories]] have been challenged by Momentum through viral videos.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://twitter.com/PeoplesMomentum/status/1101143739588923392?s=20 |title= The conspiracy behind conspiracy theories |author= |publisher= Momentum |date= 28 February 2019 |accessdate= 17 July 2019}}</ref> In the 2018 NEC elections, Momentum withdrew their support for [[Peter Willsman]] after an NEC meeting in which he described some of those \"lecturing\" the party about antisemitism as \"Trump fanatics\" who were \"making up duff information without any evidence at all\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-nec-member-pete-willsman-threatened-to-do-in-momentum-chief-jon-lansman-1.480869 |title= Labour NEC member Pete Willsman threatened to 'do in' Momentum chief Jon Lansman |newspaper= [[The Jewish Chronicle]] |date= 3 March 2019 |accessdate= 16 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/jul/31/corbyn-ally-says-jewish-trump-fanatics-make-up-antisemitism-claims |title= Corbyn ally says 'Jewish Trump fanatics making up' antisemitism claims |author= Verity Bowman and Pippa Crerar |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 31 July 2018 |accessdate= 25 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Brexit ===\nOfficially, Momentum has maintained a neutral position of the European Union and the prospect of a second referendum, instead supporting the party's position.<ref name=\"GU-Radicalmomentum\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/may/16/momentum-urges-labour-to-adopt-radical-pledges-in-next-manifesto |title= Momentum urges Labour to adopt 'radical' pledges in next manifesto |author= Heather Stewart |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 16 May 2019 |accessdate= 16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever several members of Momentum have [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|supported a second referendum]] with remain and the government's deal as options. In June 2018, the [[People's Vote]] campaign group was launched and included several former Momentum figures as well as trade union leaders. The group's launch statement was signed by [[Transport Salaried Staffs' Association|TSSA]] union general secretary [[Manuel Cortes]], economist [[Ann Pettifor]], former Momentum steering group member Michael Chessum and former CWU general secretary [[Billy Hayes (trade unionist)|Billy Hayes]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Elgot | first = Jessica | title = Pro-Corbyn group to launch drive for public vote on Brexit deal | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jun/25/pro-corbyn-group-to-launch-drive-peoples-vote-on-final-brexit-deal-labour | work = The Guardian | date = 25 June 2018 | access-date = 20 August 2018}}</ref> Polling of Momentum members in November 2018 found a majority supporting such a referendum<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-latest-momentum-labour-referendum-deal-corbyn-theresa-may-eu-a8621431.html |title= Brexit: Corbyn under pressure as Momentum members back referendum on Theresa May's deal |author= Benjamin Kentish |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 6 November 2018 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref> The left-wing, pro-European pressure group [[Another Europe Is Possible]] features Momentum members,<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/elections/2018/09/factions-fudge-and-fashion-how-momentum-went-mainstream |title= Factions, fudge and fashion: How Momentum went mainstream |author= Anoosh Chakelian |magazine= [[New Statesman]] |date= 26 September 2018 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref> such as former steering committee member Michael Chessum.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/10/new-leftwing-coalition-urges-labour-to-reject-brexit |title= New leftwing coalition urges Labour to reject Brexit |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 10 December 2018 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref> In March 2019 188 Momentum activists sent an open letter to Lansman to support a second referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://labourlist.org/2019/03/join-put-it-to-the-people-demo-momentum-activists-tell-jon-lansman/?amp |title= Join \u2018Put it to the People\u2019 demo, Momentum activists tell Jon Lansman |author= Sienna Rodgers |publisher= [[Labour List]] |date= 22 March 2019 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Reselection of MPs ===\nCritics of Corbyn within the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] have raised a concern that Momentum may encourage the [[deselection]] of MPs and councillors who disagree with it, in a process called mandatory reselection, in which all Labour politicians would be subject to internal elections.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wintour|first1=Patrick|title=Activists to harness Corbyn campaign energy with Momentum |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/08/activists-to-harness-corbyn-campaign-energy-with-momentum|accessdate=25 October 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=8 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/len-mcluskey-jeremy-corbyn-labour-party-leadership-contest-len-mccluskey-unite-deselect-mps-clive-a7315636.html |title= Union boss hints disloyal Labour MPs could be deselected after leadership election |author= Caroline Mortimer|newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 19 September 2016 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref> In 2015 Momentum denied this claim, saying \"we will not campaign for the deselection of any MP and will not permit any local Momentum groups to do so. The selection of candidates is entirely a matter for local party members and rightly so\".<ref name=\"BBC-WorriedMPs\"/><ref>{{cite news|title = The 66 Labour MPs who voted for Syria air strikes face threats of deselection and branded 'warmongers'|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-mps-who-backed-syria-air-strikes-hit-back-after-jeremy-corbyn-supporters-threaten-deselection-a6758656.html|website = The Independent <!--|date = 15 July-->|date = 3 December 2015}}</ref> The organization is however supportive of open selections, in which all members have equal influence on the selection process and are more democratically accountable rather than just socialist societies and trade unions having a strong say.<ref name=\"BBC-LPDR\"/>\n\nIn July 2018 Momentum's national coordinator Laura Parker advocated that four Labour MPs who voted down an opposition amendment to the [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018|EU withdrawal bill]] to feature a Customs Union, in line with the government, should be deselected. At the 2018 Labour Conference, Momentum's reselection reforms were supported by Corbyn.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-labour-mp-deselection-momentum-nec-vote-conference-a8521141.html |title= Jeremy Corbyn backs Momentum calls for 'changes' that could make it easier to deselect Labour MPs |author= Benjamin Kentish |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 3 September 2018 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, Momentum announced they would support Labour and Momentum members wishing to challenge sitting Labour MPs. The aim has been to encourage a younger, more [[working class]] and ethnically diverse selection of Labour MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/12/momentum-drive-labour-members-deselect-mps |title= Momentum announces drive to help Labour members deselect MPs |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 12 July 2019 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Labour Party Democracy Review ===\nFrom 2017, the Labour Party consulted on a democracy review that would see the membership gain greater voting capabilities. Momentum has been an advocate of both greater membership involvement in party decision making and in their view \"bolder reforms\".<ref name=\"BBC-LPDR\">{{cite news|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-45562446 |title= Labour's democracy review - how democratic is it? |author= Iain Watson |work= [[BBC News]] |date= 18 September 2018 |accessdate= 29 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"GU-shelvedDR\"/> Momentum has pushed for the lowering of nomination threshold for a candidate in Labour leadership elections. This is so a left-wing successor to Corbyn could contest any future election easily.<ref name=\"GU-shelvedDR\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/18/corbyns-proposals-to-transform-labour-party-parked-for-a-year |title= Corbyn's proposals to transform Labour party parked for a year |author= Heather Stewart and Jessica Elgot |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 18 September 2018 |accessdate= 20 March 2019}}</ref> The Group also supports member election council leaders.<ref name=\"Indie-tinkering\">{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-labour-party-reforms-jon-lansman-jeremy-corbyn-nec-plp-mp-a8420806.html |title= Momentum chief dismisses Labour reform proposals as 'tinkering around the edges' |author= Joe Watts |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 28 June 2018 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nMomentum tabled plans to update the way the NEC's BAME representative is chosen, with a [[one member, one vote]] election replacing the current system where a small party group decides the post. Under the group's plans, all black or minority ethnic members of the party would automatically become part of [[BAME Labour]] and have one member, one vote rights in electing their NEC representative. BAME Labour would also have an independent organisation, with its committee having direct access to its own membership list and centrally-funded finances and the ability to organise its own campaigns and events independently.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite news |last=Waugh|first=Paul|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/keith-vaz-facing-defeat-as-momentum-submits-plan-for-omov-bame-labour-reform-young-labour-autonomy-too_uk_5a58b7d0e4b02cebbfdb09ac|title=Keith Vaz Facing Loss Of Labour NEC Seat As Momentum Urges More Voting Power For Minority Ethnic Members|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nCrucial votes regarding the Democracy Review took place during the [[Labour Party Conference (UK)#2017 Brighton|2017 Labour Party Conference]] in Brighton. Momentum launched ''M.app'', a smartphone app to alert delegates to timings of key votes on the national conference floor as well as send real-time information about events and rallies.<ref name=\"theguardian3\">{{cite news |last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/21/momentum-to-launch-app-to-get-its-voters-out-at-labour-conference|title=Momentum to launch app to get its voters out at Labour conference|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 September 2017|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> The compromise motion of lowering the threshold required of local branches and local union branches to express dissatisfaction in an MP's performance from 50% to 33% passed.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Elgot | first1 = Jessica | last2 = Syal | first2 = Rajeev |title= Labour members in open revolt at union-backed party rule changes |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/23/labour-members-in-open-revolt-at-union-backed-party-reforms |work= [[The Guardian]] |date= 23 September 2018 |accessdate= 24 September 2018}}</ref> However it was announced that the democracy review was being shelved.<ref name=\"GU-shelvedDR\"/>\n\n=== Elections to Labour's Executive Committees ===\nIn the 2016 elections for the [[National Executive Committee of the Labour Party|National Executive Committee]], it emerged that Momentum, alongside the [[Centre-Left Grassroots Alliance]] and the [[Campaign for Labour Party Democracy]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pope|first1=Conor|title=Left slate in poll position for NEC race after late spate of nominations|url=http://labourlist.org/2016/07/left-slate-in-poll-position-for-nec-race-after-late-spate-of-nominations/|website=LabourList|accessdate=16 July 2016|date=16 July 2016}}</ref> were jointly backing six representatives for the [[National Executive Committee of the Labour Party|National Executive Committee]] (NEC), namely Rhea Wolfson, the former chair of the Jewish Society who replaced [[Ken Livingstone]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Doherty|first1=Rosa|title=Former Jewish Society chair backed to replace Ken Livingstone on Labour executive|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/157983/former-jewish-society-chair-backed-replace-ken-livingstone-labour-executive|accessdate=16 July 2016|work=Jewish Chronicle|date=10 May 2016}}</ref> [[Christine Shawcroft]], a senior figure in Momentum who had been a member of the NEC for fifteen years and had been briefly suspended from the party after defending [[Lutfur Rahman (politician)|Lutfur Rahman]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Syal|first1=Rajeev|title=Labour veteran suspended from party for supporting Lutfur Rahman|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/11/labour-christine-shawcroft-suspended-lutfur-rahman-tower-hamlets|accessdate=16 July 2016|work=The Guardian|date=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Cooper\">{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Charlie|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-momentum-national-executive-committee-elections-labour-party-a6930871.html|title=Jeremy Corbyn supporters urged to use Labour NEC elections to cement his hold on party|work=The Independent|date=14 March 2016|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> gaining media attention after jocular comments about dialogue with [[Daesh]] instead of [[air strikes]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Riley-Smith|first1=Ben|title=British soldiers should have 'cups of tea' with Islamic State terrorists, says Jeremy Corbyn ally|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12199570/British-soldiers-should-have-cups-of-tea-with-Islamic-State-terrorists-says-Jeremy-Corbyn-ally.html|accessdate=16 July 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=20 March 2016}}</ref> [[Peter Willsman]], [[Claudia Webbe]], [[Ann Black]], and Darren Williams.<ref name=\"Cooper\"/> All six of the candidates were elected to the six available places.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/momentum-backed-candidates-sweep-labour-8590476|title=Momentum-backed candidates sweep Labour ruling NEC elections in boost for Corbyn|first=Mikey|last=Smith|date=8 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Momentum and [[Campaign for Socialism]], their Scottish sister organisation, won 5 our of eight of the seats on the Executive Committee in [[Scottish Labour]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jamieson |first1=David |title=Momentum activists hail shift to more \"radical\" Scottish Labour with victories on executive |url=https://www.commonspace.scot/articles/10253/momentum-activists-hail-shift-more-radical-scottish-labour-victories-executive |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=[[CommonSpace]] |date=3 February 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2017 labour conference, it was announced that Labour would add three more member-elected spaces on the NEC, in response to the significant rise in membership. During the ballot period, [[Peter Willsman]] was removed from Momentum's list of recommended candidates following an allegation of antisemitism. Willsman had been recorded as describing some Jewish critics of Labour as  \"Trump fanatics\".<ref>{{cite news | last = Heffer | first = Greg | title = Jeremy Corbyn told to 'expel' ally Peter Willsman over anti-Semitism rant | url = https://news.sky.com/story/jeremy-corbyn-told-to-expel-ally-peter-willsman-over-anti-semitism-rant-11455287 | work = Sky News | date = 1 August 2018 | access-date = 2 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1= Crerar |first1= Pippa |last2= Marsh |first2= Sarah |title= Antisemitism row: Momentum drops Peter Willsman from NEC re-election list |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/01/antisemitism-row-momentum-drops-peter-willsman-from-nec-re-election-list |work= The Guardian |date= 1 August 2018 |access-date= 2 August 2018}}</ref> Three other Momentum-backed candidates were elected onto the Labour Party's NEC, namely Jon Lansman, Yasmine Dar and Rachel Garnham.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goodall|first1=Lewis|title=Crucial National Executive Committee vote transforms Labour's future|url=https://news.sky.com/story/crucial-national-executive-committee-vote-transforms-labours-future-11209060|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=Sky News|date=15 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mason|first1=Rowena|last2=Elgot|first2=Jessica|last3=Syal|first3=Rajeev|title=Momentum founder elected to NEC calls for Labour transformation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/15/momentum-backed-candidates-elected-labour-national-executive-committee|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=15 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Forsyth|first1=James|title=What does Momentum\u2019s NEC clean sweep mean for Labour?|url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2018/01/what-does-momentums-nec-clean-sweep-mean-for-labour/|website=Coffee House|publisher=The Spectator|accessdate=17 January 2018|date=15 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Momentum founder voted on to Labour NEC|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-42688288|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=BBC News|date=15 January 2018}}</ref> In April 2020, Momentum put up three candidates- two for two casual vacancies and one for a newly created BAME positionion. None of these candidates were successful.<ref name=\"PH-Keirwon\"/>\n\n== The World Transformed ==\n{{main|The World Transformed}}\nStarting in 2016, Momentum began a four-day festival called The World Transformed alongside the [[Labour Party Conference (UK)|Labour Party conference]] featuring art, music and culture alongside political discussions.<ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/><ref name=\"Huck-TWT\">{{cite web|url= https://www.huckmag.com/perspectives/opinion-perspectives/the-world-transformed/ |title= Why The World Transformed is the future of British politics |author= Nathan Akehurst |publisher= [[Huck magazine]] |date= 27 September 2017 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> This started with the Liverpool conference in 2016. One event featured a debate between [[Caroline Lucas]] co-leader of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]], [[Compass (think tank)|Compass]] chair [[Neal Lawson]] and [[Jon Lansman]] and Rhea Wolfson of Momentum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/sep/29/labour-party-of-the-future-labour-conference-momentum|title=A Labour party of the future is beginning to emerge|date=29 September 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref> In ''[[The Times]]'', [[Tony Blair]]'s former speech writer [[Philip Collins (journalist)|Philip Collins]] was positive about the event, compared to the Labour conference, \"harnessed and embraced, Momentum could be a force for good\", but wrote \"the only thing wrong with their slogan 'Jez We Can' is the first word\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Philip|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/momentum-can-be-labours-unlikely-saviour-tsd2r3ltt|title=Momentum can be Labour\u2019s unlikely saviour|work=The Times|date=29 September 2016|accessdate=10 October 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nThe World Transformed spanned nine venues across Brighton, where the Labour Party 2017 Conference was held. Many MPs attended, including [[Jeremy Corbyn]], [[John McDonnell]], [[Diane Abbott]], [[Emily Thornberry]] and [[Ed Miliband]].\n\nThe 2018 festival at the Liverpool conference had the capacity for 10,000 people to attend.<ref name=\"Sky-TWT2018\">{{cite web | last = Allegretti | first = Aubrey |title= The World Transformed: How Momentum festival is challenging for the 'mainstream' Labour conference |url= https://news.sky.com/story/the-world-transformed-how-momentum-festival-is-challenging-for-the-mainstream-labour-conference-11505328 |publisher= [[Sky News]] |date= 23 September 2018 |accessdate= 24 September 2018}}</ref> Speakers include [[2017 French presidential election|2017 French presidential candidate]] [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]] as a key-note speaker,<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/23/jean-luc-melenchon-to-speak-at-pro-corbyn-event-in-liverpool |title= Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon to speak at pro-Corbyn event in Liverpool |author= Angelique Chrisafis |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 23 September 2018 |accessdate= 24 September 2018}}</ref> as well as Jeremy Corbyn, [[Katja Kipping]] (leader of [[The Left (Germany)|Die Linke]]), [[Ralf Stegner]] ([[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]]), [[Zitto Kabwe]] (leader of [[Alliance for Change and Transparency]]) and [[Ash Sarkar]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Rodgers | first = Sienna |title= The World Transformed reveals full line-up ahead of Labour conference |url= https://labourlist.org/2018/08/the-world-transformed-reveals-full-line-up-ahead-of-labour-conference/ |publisher= [[LabourList]] |date= 8 August 2018 |accessdate= 24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Constitution and structure ==\nIn the original formation of Momentum, it used a delegate system on an executive board known as the steering committee. In late October 2016, the steering committee voted to adopt to [[One member, one vote]] (OMOV) done only on a digital instead of the delegate system- it was controversial with some on the committee and didn't pass.<ref name=\"TG-radical2016\">{{cite news|last=Gilligan|first=Andrew|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12156177/momentum-activists-jeremy-corbyn-labour-purge.html|title=Revealed: The radical hard-Left Momentum activists mounting a ruthless purge of Labour|work=The Sunday Telegraph|date=13 February 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NS-Corbynplzintervene\">{{cite news|last=Bush|first=Stephen|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/12/jeremy-corbyn-urged-intervene-momentums-feud|title=Jeremy Corbyn urged to intervene in Momentum's feud|work=New Statesman|date=6 December 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GU-Lansmanvows2016\">{{cite news |last=Syal|first=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/dec/08/corbyn-ally-vows-fight-control-momentum-labour|title=Jon Lansman vows stay in Momentum|work=The Guardian|date=8 December 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-Mmtmcivilwar2017\">{{cite news|last=Lobel|first=Mark|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38258143|title=Is Momentum at war with itself?|work=BBC News|date=9 December 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> However, a new constitution was announced on 11 January 2017 including OMOV. New members of Momentum were now required to also be members of the Labour Party, with existing Momentum members being given until July to join.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-affiliated-labour-party-jeremy-corbyn-members-must-join-a7520626.html|title=Momentum pushes activists to join Labour party to retain membership under new constitution|work=The Independent|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> Lansman initiated changes via an email. After managing to convince the steering committee, he abolished the national committee and replaced it with a Labour-only national coordinating group (NCG).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=Heather|last2=Syal|first2=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/10/momentum-shakeup-will-force-members-to-join-labour|title=Momentum shakeup will force members to join Labour|work=The Guardian|date=10 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Silvera|first=Ian|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/jon-lansman-accused-coup-momentum-unveils-new-rules-plan-join-labour-1600356|title=Jon Lansman accused of 'coup' as Momentum unveils new rules and plan to join Labour|work=International Business Times|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> A new online model of organisation without a regional structure was created with the specific intention of preventing [[far-left]] entryists dominating delegated meetings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pettitt|first=Robin|url=http://www.democraticaudit.com/2017/03/07/losing-momentum-the-power-struggles-that-are-hobbling-the-corbyn-movement/|title=Losing Momentum? The power struggles that are hobbling the Corbyn movement|work=Democratic Audit UK|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> Lansman resigned as a director of Momentum on 12 January, being replaced by Christine Shawcroft, in order to stand for election to the steering committee, it was reported.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gartside|first=Ben|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2017/01/12/jon-lansman-s-resignation-won-t-be-his-last-role-of-the-dice|title=Jon Lansman's resignation won't be his last role of the dice at Momentum|work=Politics|date=12 February 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Casalicchio|first1=Emilio |last2=Schofield|first2=Kevin|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/news/82279/blow-jon-lansman-his-own-momentum|title=Blow for Jon Lansman as his own Momentum branch votes against his 'coup'|work=Politics Home|date=12 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> The group in early March 2017 relaunched with its new constitutional structure, and a first meeting of the new NCG on 11 March and a conference on 25 March, both in Birmingham.<ref name=\"MacAskill\">{{cite news|last1=MacAskill|first1=Ewen|last2=Hacillo|first2=Alex|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/04/momentum-relaunch-factionalism-jon-lansman-labour|title=Momentum plans relaunch to end factional infighting|work=The Observer|date=4 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Membership ===\n{{Bar graph\n| title = Membership (by year)\n| float =   \n| bar_width = 20\n| width_units = em\n| data_max = 70000\n| label_type = Year\n| data_type = #\n| label1 = 2016<ref name=\"GU-Lansmanvows2016\"/> \n| data1 = 21,000\n| label2 = 2017<ref name=\"independent2\"/> \n| data2 = 31,000\n| label3 = 2018<ref name=\"GUmomuntrainscot\"/>\n| data3 = 42,000\n| label4 = 2019<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\"/>\n| data4 = 40,000\n}}\nIn 2015, the year of the group's formation, Momentum originally had 60,000 supporters who paid no subscription and 50 local groups organised.<ref name=\"BBC-WorriedMPs\">{{cite news|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34609114|title= What is Momentum, and why is it worrying Labour MPs?|author= Norman Smith |work= [[BBC News]] |date= 24 October 2015 |accessdate= 29 March 2019}}</ref> By September 2017 the organisation had grown to have 31,000 members across 170 local groups, with 15 members of staff.<ref name=\"independent2\">{{cite news |last=Farrell|first=Jeff|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/momentum-membership-jeremy-corbyn-labour-party-leader-supporters-a7988656.html|title=Momentum membership soars above 30,000 as Corbyn-supporting Labour group's influence grows|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=8 October 2017|accessdate=10 October 2017}}</ref> As of January 2018, the group had 35,000 members<ref name=\"theguardian4\">{{cite news |last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-members-growth-labour-party-jeremy-corbyn-ukip-green-conservative-membership-numbers-tory-a8166031.html/|title=Momentum surges past 35,000 members with \u2018more than 1,000 members joining every month\u2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref> With 15% membership increase since the start of 2018, by April the organisation had 40,000. Momentum has said that 95 per cent of its current funding comes from membership fees and small donations, with the average fee standing at \u00a33 a year.<ref name=\"Cowburn040418\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-membership-jeremy-corbyn-green-party-40000-labour-nec-jon-lansman-a8286706.html|title=Momentum: Corbyn-backing organisation now has 40,000 paying members, overtaking Green Party|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|date=4 April 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=4 April 2018|location=London}}</ref> In July 2018, it was reported that Momentum had 42,000 members with 92% (38,700) in England, 4% in Wales (2,000) and 3% in Scotland (1,300).<ref name=\"GUmomuntrainscot\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/26/momentum-heads-glasgow-first-scottish-training-event |title= Momentum heads to Glasgow to hold first Scottish training event |author= Libby Brooks |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 26 July 2018 |accessdate= 9 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nMomentum's membership base has been seen as being occupied by two types: young activists who joined the Labour Party during and after Corbyn's initial leadership election in 2015; and older veterens of the Labour Party left and [[far-left]] parties across Great Britain.<ref name=\"GU-Lansmanvows2016\"/><ref name=\"BBC-Mmtmcivilwar2017\"/><ref name=\"HP-Corbynsaysbenice\"/> In the original formation of Momentum, several members and activists [[Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition]], [[Left Unity (UK)|Left Unity]], the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]] (SWP), the [[Socialist Party (England and Wales)|Socialist Party]] and the [[Alliance for Workers' Liberty]] (AWL) might attach themselves to Momentum as a means to join the Labour Party.<ref name=\"TG-radical2016\"/> However, the shift in Momentum policy to only allow Labour and Momentum members to organise had a profound shift on this aspect.\n\n=== National Coordinating Group ===\nFollowing a January 2017 survey by Momentum to which over 40% of members responded, the organisation's steering committee voted by majority to introduce a new constitution.<ref name=\"Cowburn110117\"/> Eight Members' Representatives were elected: four for London and the South East; two for the Midlands, the East, the West and Wales; two for the North, Scotland and International; and four public office holders.<ref name=\"labourlist2\">{{cite news |last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|url=https://www.labourlist.org/2018/04/women-and-minorities-triumph-in-latest-momentum-election/|title=Women and minorities triumph in latest Momentum election|work= |location=London|publisher=Labour List|date=17 April 2018|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> 7,500 members took part in the election, or 34% of the membership.<ref name=\"NCGelec18\"/> In April 2018 a new set of elections took place with all four regional coordinating offices having four spaces. Over 13,000 votes were cast (35% of eligible members).<ref name=\"labourlist2\"/><ref name=\"NCGelec18\">{{cite web|url= https://peoplesmomentum.com/wp-content/uploads/Footer_Pages/Downloads/180417_NCG_Final_Results.pdf |title= National  Coordinating Group  Elections 2018 |publisher= Momentum |date= 17 April 2018 |accessdate= 2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe current composition is:<ref name=\"NCGelec18\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:95%;\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n|-\n! style=\"width=25%\" | London and the South East\n! style=\"width=25%\" | Midlands, the East, the West and Wales\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Collapsible list\n | <small>Apsana Begum</small>\n | <small>Becky Boumelha</small>\n | <small>[[Jon Lansman]]</small>\n | <small>Yannis Gourtsoyannis</small>\n}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Collapsible list\n | <small>Michael Thawe</small>\n | <small>Natasha Josette</small>\n | <small>Martin Menear</small>\n | <small>Cecile Wright</small>\n}}\n|-\n! style=\"width=25%\" | North, Scotland and International\n! style=\"width=25%\" | Public office holders\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Collapsible list\n | <small>Aneesa Akbar</small>\n | <small>Liz Smith</small>\n | <small>Elizabeth Hayden</small>\n | <small>John Taylor</small>\n}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Collapsible list\n | <small>Helen McDonald</small>\n | <small>Leigh Drennan</small>\n | <small>Joseph Ejiofor</small>\n | <small>Emina Ibrahim</small>\n}}\n|}\n\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Politics|United Kingdom|Socialism}}\n* [[Campaign for Labour Party Democracy]]\n* [[Compass (think tank)]]\n* [[Fabian Society]]\n* [[Political party affiliation in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Socialist Campaign Group]], MP grouping containing most Momentum supporting MPs\n* ''[[Tribune (magazine)|Tribune]]''\n* [[UK Uncut]]\n\n== References ==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n;Citations\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.peoplesmomentum.com/}}\n\n{{Jeremy Corbyn}}\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organisations associated with the Labour Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) factions]]\n[[Category:Left-wing politics in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jeremy Corbyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Momentum Movement}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{use British English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox organisation\n| name = Momentum\n| pronounce = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| nickname = \n| named_after = \n| image = Momentum logo (2017).png\n| image_border = \n| size = 220px\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| map = \n| msize = \n| malt = \n| mcaption = \n| map2 = \n| abbreviation = \n| motto = A new kind of politics\n| predecessor = \n| merged = \n| successor = \n| formation = {{start date and age|2015|10|08|df=y}}\n| founder = [[Jon Lansman]]\n| extinction = \n| merger = \n| type = \n| status = \n| purpose = \n| professional_title = \n| headquarters = \n| location_city = [[London]]\n| location_country = England\n| location = [[Finsbury Park (area)|Finsbury Park]]<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/><ref name=\"Vice-secretweapon\"/>\n| coords = \n| region = {{plainlist|\n*[[Great Britain]]\n*''[[Labour International]]''}}\n| services = \n| products = \n| methods = \n| fields = \n| membership = 40,000<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\"/>\n| membership_year = 2019\n| language = \n| owner = \n| sec_gen = \n| leader_title = Chair\n| leader_name = Jon Lansman\n| leader_title2 = Vice-Chair\n| leader_name2 = {{plainlist|\n*Emina Ibrahim\n*Cecile Wright}}\n| leader_title3 = National coordinator\n| leader_name3 = ''Vacant''\n| leader_title4 = Digital officer\n| leader_name4 = \n| board_of_directors = {{plainlist|\n*Jon Lansman\n*[[Sam Tarry]]\n*Anthony Kearns\n*[[Elizabeth Kennedy Hayden|Elizabeth Hayden]]\n*Cecile Wright}}\n| key_people = \n| main_organ = \n| parent_organisation = \n| subsidiaries = \n| affiliations = {{plainlist|class=nowrap|\n*[[Centre-Left Grassroots Alliance]]\n*[[Campaign for Socialism]] (in Scotland)\n*Welsh Labour Grassroots (in Wales)}}\n| budget = \n| budget_year = \n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = \n| disbursements = \n| expenses = \n| expenses_year = \n| endowment = \n| endowment_year = \n| staff = 13<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/>\n| staff_year = 2019\n| volunteers = \n| volunteers_year = \n| website = {{url|https://peoplesmomentum.com/}}\n| remarks = \n| formerly = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Momentum''' is a British political organisation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-controversial-left-wing-group-to-debate-joining-labour-in-boost-to-jeremy-corbyn-a6779916.html|title=Momentum group may join Labour to boost Jeremy Corbyn|last=McTague|first=Tom|date=19 December 2015|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> It has been described as a [[grassroots movement]] supportive of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]],<ref name=bush2015/><ref name=smith2015>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34609114|title=What is Momentum, and why is it worrying Labour MPs?|work=BBC News|date=24 October 2015|author=Norman Smith}}</ref><ref name=\"JonStone 8Oct Indy\">{{cite news|last1=Stone|first1=Jon|title=Jeremy Corbyn's leadership campaign sets up new local activist network called 'Momentum'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyns-leadership-campaign-sets-up-new-local-activist-network-called-momentum-a6686191.html|accessdate=23 November 2015|work=The Independent|date=8 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011181318/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyns-leadership-campaign-sets-up-new-local-activist-network-called-momentum-a6686191.html|archivedate=11 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> it is seen to represent the [[left-wing (politics)|left]] of the party.{{refn|group=n|name=left|\n* {{cite news |date= 23 December 2019 |title= Ed Miliband to join review of Labour's election failure |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50888060 |work= BBC News |access-date= 11 January 2020}}\n* {{cite news |date= 12 December 2019 |title= Corbyn blames Brexit as Labour Party rifts erupt following dismal general election results |url= https://www.itv.com/news/2019-12-12/labour-blame-brexit-dominated-campaign-as-poll-predicts-disastrous-defeat/ |work= ITV News |access-date= 11 January 2020}}\n* <ref name=\"Indy-JohnthankMomentum\"/>\n* {{cite news |last= Wright |first= Oliver |date= 31 July 2018 |title= Labour\u2019s Momentum defeated in founder\u2019s constituency |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/labour-s-momentum-defeated-in-founder-s-constituency-vnfg6svkl |work= The Times |access-date= 11 January 2020}}}}\n\nIt was founded in 2015 by [[Jon Lansman]], Adam Klug, Emma Rees and [[James Schneider]], following the successful campaign for Jeremy Corbyn to become the Leader of the Labour Party. The current officers of Momentum Campaign (Services) Ltd are:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09654873/officers|title=Momentum Campaign (Services) Ltd|publisher=[[Companies House]]|accessdate=2020-01-08}}</ref> Lansman, [[Sam Tarry MP]], [[Mossley Hill (ward)|Mossley Hill]] Councillor [[Elizabeth Kennedy Hayden|Elizabeth Hayden]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whocanivotefor.co.uk/person/43536/elizabeth-kennedy-hayden|title=Elizabeth Kennedy Hayden|publisher=WhoCanIVoteFor?|accessdate=2020-01-08}}</ref> solicitor Anthony Kearns,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://solicitors.lawsociety.org.uk/person/295168/anthony-paul-kearns|title=Anthony Paul Kearns|publisher=[[Law Society]]|accessdate=2020-01-08}}</ref> and Professor Cecile Wright of the [[University of Nottingham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/news/expertiseguide/sociology-social-policy/professor-cecile-yvonne-wright-.aspx|title=Professor Cecile Yvonne Wright |publisher=[[University of Nottingham]]|accessdate=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation has polarised Labour politicians and journalists since its inception. Some have compared it to the [[Militant tendency]] within the Labour party; however, others have praised its grassroots engagement as well as its effective and virally spread but low budget information videos, such as those used in the 2017 general election campaign. Since January 2017, all Momentum members must also be or become members of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"Cowburn110117\"/> The organisation had 40,000 members in 2019.<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\"/> It also has close links with [[The World Transformed]].\n\n== Background ==\nMomentum was founded in 2015 by [[Jon Lansman]] along with the original national organisers, Adam Klug, Emma Rees and [[James Schneider]], four weeks after [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s [[2015 Jeremy Corbyn Labour Party leadership campaign|successful campaign]] for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leadership.<ref name=G8815>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/08/jeremy-corbyn-leadership-campaign-new-social-movement-momentum|title=Jeremy Corbyn leadership campaign gives rise to new social movement|author=Patrick Wintour|date=8 October 2015|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=bush2015>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2015/10/labour-mps-are-worried-about-momentum-should-they-be|title=Labour MPs are worried about Momentum. Should they be?|magazine=New Statesman|date= 23 October 2015|author=Stephen Bush}}</ref><ref name=\"RP-Howitallcametobe\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.redpepper.org.uk/how-momentum-came-together/|title=How Momentum came together|last=Ghadiali|first=Ashish|date=16 January 2018|work=Red Pepper|access-date=}}</ref> Local groups formed in support for Corbyn's leadership, uniting different factions of [[British Left|the left across Britain]] behind the movement to get him elected.<ref name=\"RP-Howitallcametobe\"/> Lansman was active in [[Tony Benn]]'s [[1981 Labour Party deputy leadership election|1981 deputy leadership bid]].<ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/> Beyond their support for Corbyn, Momentum has three primary goals: to win elections for Labour, to create a socialist Labour government, and help build a wider social movement.<ref name=\"Vice-secretweapon\"/> Corbyn was positive about Momentum following its formation, saying in 2016: \u201cI see Momentum as a social movement. A movement that will campaign on all of these issues. But above all, excite and unite people to come together, to come together to challenge injustice, inequality and social exclusion. Bring people together to achieve things together. That is what is makes us [Labour] so different from every other political party in this country.\u201d<ref name=\"HP-Corbynsaysbenice\">{{cite news|last=Simons|first=Ned|title=Jeremy Corbyn tells Momentum to unite amid internal rift as aides plot leadership relaunch|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-corbyn-tells-momentum-disunity-is-our-enemy-amid-internal-rift_uk_5853261ae4b0acb6e4b7d4f1|work=HuffPost|date=16 December 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nWith its formation, Momentum drew inspiration from [[Syriza]] in Greece and [[Podemos (Spanish political party)|Podemos]] in Spain, both of which were fed by practical, grassroots organising to counter the effects of austerity cuts.<ref name=\"RP-Howitallcametobe\"/><ref name=\"theguardian2\">{{cite news |last=Bulman|first=May|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/jun/14/momentum-grassroots-democracy-labour-unstoppable|title=Labour Party membership soars by 35,000 since general election|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=13 June 2017|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> As the movement has evolved, it has also benefited from ideas from other campaigns that operate on a [[left-wing]] or [[Progressivism|progressive]] platform such as in the United States, with the [[Bernie Sanders]] campaign to become presidential candidate for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic party]] in [[Bernie Sanders 2016 presidential campaign|2016]]<ref name=\"GUberniecampaign\"/> and [[Bernie Sanders 2020 presidential campaign|2020]]<ref name=\"GU-DSAsupport\"/> or [[Beto O'Rourke]]'s [[2018 United States Senate election in Texas|campaign to become the Democratic Senator]] for [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/07/momentum-to-examine-texas-us-senate-race-for-tips-for-labour-campaigns |title= Momentum to examine US Senate race for tips for Labour campaigns |author= Dan Sabbagh |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 7 November 2018 |accessdate= 28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Relationship with other organisations ===\nIn 2016 the Scottish left-wing organisation [[Campaign for Socialism]] (CfS) formed a partnership with Momentum. Though they are maintained as separate organisations they share membership and resources. Since then, the membership of CfS has grown from 400 in 2015 to 1,418 by 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rodgers |first1=Sienna |title=Corbynsceptics celebrate as Pam Duncan-Glancy is reselected in Glasgow North |url=https://labourlist.org/2018/05/corbynsceptics-celebrate-as-pam-duncan-glancy-is-reselected-in-glasgow-north/ |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=[[LabourList]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Courea |first1=Eleni |title=\"Momentum needs to reflect the different regions\": Meet the Scottish Corbynites |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2019/05/momentum-needs-reflect-different-regions-meet-scottish-corbynites |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=[[New Statesman]] |language=en}}</ref>\nWelsh Labour Grassroots is the sister organisation of Momentum in Wales.<ref>{{cite news |date= 13 April 2020 |title= Coronavirus: Labour group calls for distinct Welsh response |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52272918 |work= BBC News |access-date= 15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Williamson |first1=David |title=Mark Drakeford tipped to be next Welsh Labour leader |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/mark-drakeford-tipped-next-welsh-14498381 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=walesonline |publisher=[[Reach plc]] |date=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Early infiltration from the far-left ===\n\nMembers of the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] (PLP) had raised concerns that parties on the [[far-left]] of British politics including the [[Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition]], [[Left Unity (UK)|Left Unity]], the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]] (SWP), the [[Socialist Party (England and Wales)|Socialist Party]] and the [[Alliance for Workers' Liberty]] (AWL) might join Momentum as a means to influence the Labour Party.<ref name=\"Guardian: Momentum\">{{cite news|last1 = Wintour|first1 = Patrick|title = Unite challenges expulsion of alleged Trotskyists from Labour party|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/23/unite-challenges-expulsion-of-alleged-trotskyists-from-labour-party|accessdate = 25 October 2015|work = The Guardian|date = 24 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-WorriedMPs\"/> However, Momentum was mired by the joining of members of these groups and the disruption they caused in the democratisation and organisation of Momentum.<ref name=\"NS-Corbynplzintervene\"/><ref name=\"GU-Lansmanvows2016\"/><ref name=\"BBC-Mmtmcivilwar2017\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fisher|first1=Lucy|last2=Savage|first2=Michael|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hard-left-corbynites-dismissed-as-softies-rbbhsqdqt|title=Hard-left Corbynites dismissed as softies|work=The Times|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref> An example was Jill Mountford, a long established member of AWL who was accused of bullying with Momentum.<ref name=\"Cowburn110117\">{{cite news |last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-affiliated-labour-party-jeremy-corbyn-members-must-join-a7520626.html|title=Momentum pushes activists to join Labour party to retain membership under new constitution|work=The Independent|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref> There was some consideration in these groups to disband and support Momentum- such as Left Unity in 2015 members proposed a motion to merge with Momentum several times, to no success.<ref>{{cite web|title = Left Unity party to consider joining Labour|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/19/left-unity-party-ken-loach-to-consider-joining-labour-jeremy-corbyn|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 6 December 2015|first = Patrick Wintour Political|last = editor}}</ref>\n\nThe movement has drawn comparisons to [[Militant (Trotskyist group)|the Militant Tendency]], or Militant, a group that was expelled by Labour under [[Neil Kinnock]] in the 1980s. Labour MP [[Owen Smith]] accused Momentum of using the same tactics as Militant such as threatening to deselect Labour MPs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2016/09/owen-smith-evokes-1980s-struggle-as-he-brands-momentum-a-party-within-a-party/|title=Owen Smith evokes 1980s struggle as he brands Momentum \"a party within a party\" |work= [[Labour List]] |date=16 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref> These concerns were echoed by former [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|deputy Labour leader]] Roy Hattersley.<ref name=\"Ob-Subversion\">{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/dec/02/labour-faces-subversion-momentum-far-left-roy-hattersley-watford-byelection |title= Labour faces subversion by Momentum and far left, says Roy Hattersley |author= Toby Helm and Michael Savage |work= [[The Observer]] |publisher= [[The Guardian]] |date= 2 December 2017 |accessdate= 20 March 2019}}</ref> [[Oliver Kamm]] of ''[[The Times]]'' wrote in October 2015: \"Like the Trotskyists of a generation ago Momentum is an [[entryism|entrist]] organisation that's parasitic on the Labour host. This time, though, the far left has managed to gain control of the party structures and is intent on making life tough for Labour MPs\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kamm |first=Oliver |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/thunderer/article4584025.ece |title=The real Labour party must refuse to work with Corbyn |work=The Times|location=London|date=13 October 2015|accessdate=26 July 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref> A Labour councillor in Liverpool in 2019 had commented about the presence of Momentum in the city by saying: \"I think Momentum in Liverpool is a mask for Militant. There are decent Momentum people and then there are the others who have their own agenda\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/feb/23/liverpool-wavertree-labour-constituency-antisemitism-luciana-berger-derek-hatton |title= Anger, denial and prejudice fester on the streets of Liverpool Wavertree |author= Andrew Anthony |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 23 February 2019 |accessdate= 28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nMomentum itself and a number of political commentators characterise their supposed relationship with other groups as unfair.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/is-momentum-a-return-to-the-old-days-of-labour-s-militant-tendency-a6782621.html|title=Is Momentum a return to the old days of Labour\u2019s militant tendency?|date=22 December 2015|publisher=}}</ref> In October 2015, Momentum stated would resist such entryism.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2015/10/pro-corbyn-group-momentum-vows-resist-swp-infiltration|title=Pro-Corbyn group Momentum vows to resist SWP \"infiltration\"|date=16 October 2015|author=George Eaton|author-link=George Eaton (journalist)|magazine=New Statesman}}</ref><ref name=\"HP-Schneider2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/10/20/momentum-labour-jeremy-corbyn-deselection_n_8337282.html |title=Momentum Is Not A 'Shadowy' Group With A 'Hit List' Of Labour MPs, Says Leading Organiser |publisher=[[Huffington Post]] |accessdate= 9 April 2020}}</ref> Author and journalist [[Michael Crick]] opposes the comparison to Militant, stating that \"the rise of Jeremy Corbyn can be attributed more to the phenomenon of '[[Corbynmania]]' than to hard-left entrism\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Crick|first1=Michael|title=Militant|date=10 March 2016|publisher=Biteback Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-1-78590-029-7}} (back cover)</ref> Former Labour MP [[Peter Kilfoyle]], who had acted as enforcer for the Labour leadership against Militant on Merseyside in the 1980s as the party's North West Regional Organiser, also rejected the comparison, instead describing Momentum as fulfilling the same kind of role on the left of the party as [[Progress (organisation)|Progress]] did on the right.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/membership/2016/aug/05/peter-kilfoyle-liverpool-labour-momentum-jeremy-corbyn |title=Peter Kilfoyle: 'Something is going wrong in Liverpool' |last=MacAskill |first=Ewen|author-link=Ewen MacAskill |date=5 August 2016 |website=[[theguardian.com]]|access-date=28 July 2018}}</ref> In December 2015, Labour's then deputy leader [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] made a cynical commentary on the ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme about the group: \"They look like a bit of a rabble to me, but I don't think they are a problem for the Labour Party\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Watt|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/dec/04/labour-split-exposed-tom-watson-momentum-rabble-livingstone|title=Labour split exposed as Tom Watson describes Momentum as a 'rabble'|work=The Guardian|date=4 December 2015|accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref> Schneider commented in response to this accusation as such: \"The purpose of Momentum is not to have internal factional battles, it's to look outside\".<ref name=\"TG2015deslect\">{{cite news|last1=Gilligan|first1=Andrew|title=The Corbyn hardcore plotting to deselect Labour moderates|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11981745/The-Corbyn-hardcore-plotting-to-deselect-Labour-moderates.html|accessdate=23 November 2015|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== International relationships ===\nMomentum has built ties with other political organisations across North America and Europe. They have collaborated with the Canadian [[Leap Manifesto|Leap movement]], the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]]'s [[Young Socialists in the SPD|Young Socialists]],<ref name=\"SPD activist want Momentum\">{{cite news |title=SPD activists seek help of Momentum to dash German coalition deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/24/germany-spd-social-democratic-party-coalition-deal-momentum-cdu |newspaper=The Guardian |author= Philip Oltermann |date= 24 January 2018 |access-date= 28 July 2018}}</ref> the [[Democratic Socialists of America]]<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/26/momentum-plan-tap-into-new-us-socialism-labour-conference |title= How Momentum is tapping into the new US socialism |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 26 September 2018 |accessdate= 9 November 2018}}</ref> and similar organisations in Greece. In 2018, Rees and Klug went on a ten-week lecture tour of the United States to educate progressive activists and members of the [[National Nurses United]] union on political campaigning techniques as well as advising Real Justice.<ref name=\"Sights on Donald Trump\">{{cite web |title=Exclusive: Momentum founders turn their sights on Donald Trump |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/momentum-founders-turn-their-sights-on-donald-trump/ |publisher=[[i (newspaper)|i]] |author= Nigel Morris |date= 27 July 2018 |access-date= 28 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Campaigning history ==\n=== Early formation ===\nMomentum undertook a campaign called Democracy SOS to address the problem of the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Conservative-Liberal Democrat government]] implementing the changes to the electoral register to an [[Individual Electoral Registration]] system. The Electoral Commission recommended that the program be implemented a year later than it was. The EC believed, based on 2015 records, that there were eight million people eligible for registration but not registered and 1.9 million people previously registered who have been dropped off by the changes. Momentum utilized their network to campaign in towns and university campuses to encourage people to register.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyns-momentum-activist-network-announces-mass-voter-registration-campaign-a6698691.html |title=Jeremy Corbyn's Momentum activist network announces mass voter registration campaign|author=Jon Stone|date=19 October 2015|work=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://democracy-sos.peoplesmomentum.com/|title=Democracy SOS \u2013 Momentum|publisher=Democracy SOS}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.opendemocracy.net/uk/alison-whyte/democracy-sos-stop-electoral-register-cull |title= Democracy SOS - stop the electoral register cull |author= Alison Whyte |publisher= [[Open Democracy]] |date= 23 October 2015 |accessdate= 17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Labour's former shadow chancellor [[John McDonnell]] praise Momentum for their work in the [[2016 United Kingdom local elections|local elections that May]]. They coordinated activists from Brighton and London to areas like [[Hastings]], [[Crawley]] and [[Harlow]]; activists in the [[North West England|North West]] were directed to [[West Lancashire]].<ref name=\"Indy-JohnthankMomentum\">{{cite news |last= Stone |first= Jon |date= 10 May 2016 |title= John McDonnell says Momentum activists helped drive Labour\u2019s better-than-expected election result |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-says-left-wing-momentum-activists-drove-labour-s-better-than-expected-election-result-a7022816.html |work= The Independent |access-date= 11 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nAfter the [[2017 Stoke-on-Trent Central by-election|Stoke-on-Trent Central]] and [[2017 Copeland by-election|Copeland by-elections]] were called, Momentum mobilised its large activist base to campaign for both. Momentum launched two pieces of technology to help this, a Phone Banking web application called Grassroots Now (previously used in Corbyn's Labour leadership election campaigns in 2015 and 2016) and a carpooling web application to help activists travel to the campaign days from across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peoplesmomentum.com/by_elections|title=By-elections|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2017/02/momentum-carpool-brings-activists-to-crucial-by-election-campaigns|title=Momentum carpool brings activists to crucial by-election campaigns - LabourList|date=10 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2017/01/momentum-seeks-to-move-on-from-internal-fueds-and-help-deliver-by-election-victories|title=Momentum seeks to move on from feuds and help deliver by-election victories - LabourList|date=26 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Ultimately, Labour Party candidate in Stoke-on-trent Gareth Snell won while in the traditional Labour stronghold of Copeland the Labour candidate Gillian Troughton lost to her Conservative opponent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39064149|title=Tories in historic by-election Copeland win|date=24 February 2017|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 general election campaign ===\n{{main|2017 United Kingdom general election}}\nIn the run-up to the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|general election on 8 June 2017]], Momentum worked to mobilise voters and encourage volunteers to canvass on behalf of Labour. Their campaign strategy was to target marginal seats rather than defend safe seats.<ref name=\"Vice-secretweapon\"/><ref name=\"Jacobin-makeCorbynPM2019\"/> As part of this ambition the group created 'MyNearestMarginal.com', a website which allows voters to search for campaigning events in marginal constituencies closest to them;<ref name=\"WiredMCM2019\"/> and ElectionDayPledge.com, where voters can pledge to volunteer on Polling Day, were created. Momentum also worked with organisers from [[Bernie Sanders]]' [[Bernie Sanders 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]] to hold training sessions for volunteers, such as persuasive conversation training.<ref name=\"GUberniecampaign\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/30/the-us-sanders-campaigners-lending-corybn-hand-bernie-momentum|title=The US Bernie Sanders campaigners lending Jeremy Corbyn a hand|last=Khomami|first=Nadia|date=20 May 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=30 May 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/> It drafted in senior figures from Sanders' campaign, including Erika Uyterhoeven, formerly a national director for outer-state organising,<ref name=\"independent1\">{{cite news |last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-what-happens-jeremy-corbyn-post-general-election-2017-labour-defeat-hard-left-wing-a7777506.html|title=Momentum: What happens to the Jeremy Corbyn-backing organisation after the general election?|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref> Grayson Lookner, Jeremy Parkin and Kim McMurray.<ref name=\"theweek\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/general-election-2017/85501/how-momentum-helped-sway-the-general-election|title=How Momentum helped sway the general election|magazine=[[The Week]]|date=12 June 2017|accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThey had an effective social media presence with many of their low-budget videos becoming virally spread. One example was \"Daddy, do you hate me?\", which was watched by 12.7 million unique Facebook users- at the time more than one in three in the UK.<ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/> By the end of the election campaign, Momentum reached 51 million views on all of their videos.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/>\n\nMembership of the organisation increased by 1,500 within four days of the general election<ref name=\"theguardian2\"/> and by another 3,000 within two months.<ref name=\"newstatesman1\">{{cite magazine |last1=Murugesu|first1=Jason|last2=Varghese|first2=Sanjana|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/2017/08/how-momentum-activists-are-learning-win-over-tory-voters|title=How Momentum activists are learning to win over Tory voters|magazine=[[New Statesman]]|date=15 August 2017|accessdate=15 August 2017}}</ref> The organisation's [[Facebook]] page reached 23.7 million views and videos were watched by 12.7 million unique users. In total, Momentum spent less than \u00a32,000 advertising on the social media platform.<ref name=\"independent1\"/> In May 2017, [[Noam Chomsky]] claimed the future of the party must lie with the left of the party and Momentum, saying: \"The constituency of the Labour Party, the new participants, the Momentum group and so on, [...] if there is to be a serious future for the Labour Party that is where it is in my opinion\".<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite news |last=Asthana|first=Anushka|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/10/labour-partys-future-lies-with-momentum-says-noam-chomsky|title=Labour party's future lies with Momentum, says Noam Chomsky|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 May 2017|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> On polling day, 10,000 Momentum activists knocked on an estimated 1.2 million doors in the UK.<ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/>\n\nThe general election led to Labour losing five seats to the Conservatives, but Labour won 28 from them, as well as six from the SNP and two from the Lib Dems.  Almost every constituency that Momentum targeted was gained by Labour.<ref name=\"WiredMCM2019\"/> After the general election, Giles Kenningham, former Conservative Party director of communications, said in July 2017: \"Labour have used Momentum to devastating effect\".<ref name=\"ft-devestating\">{{cite news |last=Bond|first=David|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d1c854f0-4cea-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43|title=Labour\u2019s slick online campaign outguns Tory press|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> Later in the month, [[Michael Gove]], Conservative MP said: \"The Conservative Party can learn a lot from Momentum\".<ref name=\"inews\">{{cite news |last=Landin|first=Conrad|url=https://www.inews.co.uk/essentials/news/politics/michael-gove-conservatives-can-learn-lot-momentum/|title=Labour\u2019s slick online campaign outguns Tory press|work= |location= |publisher=[[i (newspaper)|i]]|date=25 June 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> In August, it was announced that the [[Communication Workers Union (UK)|Communications Workers Union]] will formally affiliate to Momentum after its ruling executive voted unanimously in favour to join the organisation.<ref name=\"newstatesman2\">{{cite magazine|last=Bush|first=Stephen|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2017/08/britains-largest-communications-union-affiliate-momentum|title=Britain's largest communications union to affiliate to Momentum|magazine=[[New Statesman]]|date=23 August 2017|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref> A former critic of the Labour left and Corbyn, [[John McTernan]], joined Momentum in summer 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mairs|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/88199/watch-arch-blairite-john-mcternan-joins-momentum|title=WATCH: Arch-Blairite John McTernan joins Momentum|publisher=Politics Home|date=13 August 2017|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref> In summer 2017, Adam Klug resigned as national co-ordinator following the snap general election. In October 2017, Emma Rees, a co-founder of the group, stood down as national co-ordinator. Laura Parker who left her role as Jeremy Corbyn's political secretary before the national conference replaced Rees as national co-ordinator.<ref name=\"labourlist1\">{{cite news |last=Edwards|first=Peter|url=https://www.labourlist.org/2017/10/exclusive-new-shake-up-at-momentum-as-two-top-organisers-resign/|title=Momentum membership soars above 30,000 as Corbyn-supporting Labour group's influence grows|work= |location= |publisher=Labour List|date=24 October 2017|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] (EC) announced that Momentum had been fined \u00a316,700 for multiple breaches of electoral law, including failing to accurately report donations during the general election period.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=6 March 2019 |title=Momentum fined by Electoral Commission for multiple breaches of electoral law |publisher= |url=https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/i-am-a/journalist/electoral-commission-media-centre/party-and-election-finance-to-keep/momentum-fined-by-electoral-commission-for-multiple-breaches-of-electoral-law |website=electoralcommission.org.uk |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> The fine for not submitting an accurate spending return was the biggest issued to a non-party campaign.<ref name=\"BBCECruling2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47468571|title=Momentum fined over election spending|work=[[BBC News]]|date=2019-03-06|access-date=2019-03-06|language=en-GB}}</ref> Though the group was initially investigated by the EC with the concern that they had overspent, the EC found this was not the case.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-fined-electoral-commission-law-corbyn-labour-a8809666.html |title= Momentum fined more than \u00a316,000 for multiple breaches of electoral law during 2017 election |author= Ashley Cowburn |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 6 March 2019 |accessdate= 14 March 2019}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=April 2019}} Momentum's then national treasurer Puru Miah, a councilor in [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets|Tower Hamlets]], commented \"we have put in place comprehensive systems so we can fully adhere to regulations\".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.eastlondonadvertiser.co.uk/news/politics/cllr-puru-miah-admits-momentum-s-election-offences-1-5927212 |title= Tower Hamlets councilor holds his hands up to Momentum\u2019s election offences over cash payments as its treasurer |author= Mike Brooke |publisher= [[East London Advertiser]] |date= 8 March 2019 |accessdate= 20 March 2019}}</ref> In April 2020 Momentum published a report disecting their performance in both the 2017 and 19 general elections- saying that constituencies such as [[Broxtowe (UK Parliament constituency)|Broxtowe]], [[Hendon (UK Parliament constituency)|Hendon]], [[Morley and Outwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Morley and Outwood]], [[Southampton Itchen (UK Parliament constituency)|Southampton Itchen]], [[Pudsey (UK Parliament constituency)|Pudsey]], [[Thurrock (UK Parliament constituency)|Thurrock]] and [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]] could have been won with the enhanced ground support they had reached by 2019.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/>\n\n=== The Unseat! campaign and expansion into local government (2017\u20132019) ===\nIn aftermath of the 2017 general election, Momentum mobilised the Unseat campaign with prominent partners such as [[Owen Jones (writer)|Owen Jones]], targeting constituencies where prominent Conservative MPs have a small majority and could be susceptible to a Labour win at the next general election. Thousands have attended Unseat events in seats held by then Education Secretary [[Justine Greening]] ([[Putney (UK Parliament constituency)|Putney]]), former DWP Secretary [[Iain Duncan Smith]] ([[Chingford and Woodford Green (UK Parliament constituency)|Chingford and Woodford Green]]) and current Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] ([[Uxbridge and South Ruislip (UK Parliament constituency)|Uxbridge and South Ruislip]]).<ref>{{cite web|url= https://labourlist.org/2018/05/owen-jones-momentum-campaigning-was-crucial-to-labours-local-election-gains/ |title= Owen Jones: Momentum campaigning was crucial to Labour\u2019s local election gains |author= [[Owen Jones (writer)|Owen Jones]] |publisher= [[Labour List]] |date= 8 May 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/08/03/unseatboris-momentum-sets-training-camps-get-rid-foreign-secretary/ |title= #UnseatBoris: Momentum sets up training camps to get rid of the Foreign Secretary |author= Helena Horton |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date= 3 August 2017 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://leftfootforward.org/2017/08/revealed-the-eight-tories-momentum-are-now-gearing-up-to-unseat/ |title= Revealed: The eight Tories Momentum are now gearing up to unseat |author= Josiah Mortimer |publisher= [[Left Foot Forward]] |date= 16 August 2017 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/2018/08/chingford-corbynite-faiza-shaheen-her-mission-oust-iain-duncan-smith |title= The Chingford Corbynite: Faiza Shaheen on her mission to oust Iain Duncan Smith |author= George Eaton|author-link=George Eaton (journalist)|magazine= [[New Statesman]] |date= 8 August 2018 |accessdate= 27 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/news/labour-and-momentum-rally-to-target-paul-maynard-s-marginal-seat-1-9282395 |title= Labour and Momentum rally to target Paul Maynard's marginal seat |author= James Graves|newspaper= [[Blackpool Gazette]] |date= 2 August 2018 |accessdate= 27 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.swindonadvertiser.co.uk/news/16161361.activists-aim-to-unseat-the-tories-in-may/ |title= Owen Jones and Momentum descend on Swindon to \u2018unseat Tory council\u2019 |author= Thomas Haworth |publisher= [[Swindon Advisor]] |date= 16 April 2018 |accessdate= 27 February 2019}}</ref> The campaign motivated Duncan Smith to contact local Conservative associations to organise activists to run counter campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/alexspence/these-leaked-whatsapp-chats-show-iain-duncan-smiths-pleas |title= These Leaked WhatsApp Chats Show Iain Duncan Smith\u2019s Pleas For Help After His Seat Was Targeted By Momentum |author= Alex Spence |publisher= [[Buzzfeed News]] |date= 20 March 2018 |accessdate= 27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nBecause the Labour Party believed another [[Next United Kingdom general election|snap general election]] was likely, the party ran the selection procedure to have a slate of parliamentary candidates in place for the 96 marginal constituencies- Momentum backed several candidates.<ref name=\"GU2018marginals\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/19/momentum-backed-labour-candidates-to-contest-most-marginal-seats |title= Momentum-backed Labour candidates to contest most-marginal seats |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 19 March 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019 }}</ref> By January 2019, it was recorded that over half of their 67 selections were successful in becoming candidates.<ref name=\"GU2019marginals\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/05/unite-momentum-dominate-labour-selections-candidates-key-marginals |title= Unite and Momentum candidates dominate Labour\u2019s selection races |author= Eleni Courea |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 5 January 2019 |accessdate= 25 February 2019 }}</ref> Additionally, Momentum wished to influence the new manifesto by promising to introduce a four-day working week and a [[Green New Deal]]- an idea of mass state investment to address climate change.<ref name=\"GU-Radicalmomentum\"/>\n\nMomentum established a candidate network in which they provide support to new councillors, encourage women to stand, give them spaces to discuss policy and also training on the success of Labour controlled councils like [[Salford City Council|Salford]] and [[Preston City Council|Preston]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/feb/06/momentum-network-trains-councillors-to-fight-local-elections |title= Momentum sets up councillor network to target local elections |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 6 February 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> Notable Momentum-backed selections from the [[2018 United Kingdom local elections|2018 local elections]] was [[Rokhsana Fiaz]] for [[Mayor of Newham]], who successfully became mayor on an increased majority.<ref name=\"GU2018marginals\"/> Trafford Labour party's leader cited Momentum as a key reason for why Labour gained seats in borough.<ref name=\"LFF-2018LE\">{{cite web|url= https://leftfootforward.org/2018/05/no-momentum-didnt-cost-labour-victory-last-night/ |title= No, Momentum didn\u2019t cost Labour a victory in the local elections |author= Josiah Mortimer |publisher= [[Left Foot Forward]] |date= 4 May 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> A Momentum-supported councillor Joseph Ejiofor became the leader of [[Haringey London Borough Council]] after the elections in London.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/momentum-leader-takes-over-haringey-labour-council-despite-party-vote-a3834431.html |title= Momentum leader takes over Haringey Labour council despite party vote |author= Kate Proctor |newspaper= [[London Evening Standard]] |date= 9 May 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, following the resignation of 9 Labour members of parliament, with 8 becoming members of the [[centrism|centrist]] [[The Independent Group|Independent Group]] with resigning Conservatives,<ref name=GU-TIG>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/02/rebel-labour-mps-set-to-quit-party-and-form-centre-group|title=Rebel Labour MPs set to quit party and form centre group|last=Helm|first=Toby|date=18 February 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=18 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218134948/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/02/rebel-labour-mps-set-to-quit-party-and-form-centre-group|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Momentum began to organise resources and activists to campaign in these seats. They wished to initiate public pressure from their constituents to trigger by-elections. The group raised \u00a315,000 from their activists in the hours after their split to contribute to funding this campaign.<ref name=\"ind-byelectionsnow\">{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-split-momentum-campaign-resignations-corbyn-independent-group-a8790121.html |title= Momentum launches campaigning drive against ex-Labour MPs who have joined Independent Group\n|author= Ashley Cowburn |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 22 February 2019 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> On 19 March, the group organized 100 activists in [[Streatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Streatham]], [[Chuka Umunna]]'s constituency, with Owen Jones, [[Diane Abbott]] and [[Ash Sarkar]] speaking to the activists at a rally.<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/elections/2019/03/momentum-has-begun-campaigning-unseat-tig-mps |title= Momentum has begun campaigning to unseat TIG MPs |author= Eleni Courea |magazine= [[New Statesman]] |date= 19 March 2019 |accessdate= 20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 United Kingdom local elections|2019 local elections]], James Driscoll was selected as Labour candidate for the inaugural  [[2019 North of Tyne mayoral election|first North of Tyne mayoral election]] became a notable Momentum-backed selection.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/jamie-driscoll-north-tyne-mayor-15860074 |title= Who is Jamie Driscoll? Labour's left-wing North of Tyne mayoral candidate |author= Sean Seddon |publisher= [[The Chronicle and the Journal]] |date= 21 February 2019 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> Driscoll won this election with 56.1% of the vote in the second round. In addition, [[Brighton and Hove City Council]], where Momentum backed 12 Labour candidates<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/19/brighton-well-organised-momentum-group-shifts-focus-to-local-elections |title= Brighton: well-organised Momentum group shifts focus to local elections |author= Dan Sabbagh |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 19 March 2018 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> and [[Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council|Sandwell council]] were key focals point for Momentum.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Madeley |first1=Pete |title='Completely anti-democratic': Tom Watson slams 'hard-left takeover' of Sandwell Council |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/politics/2019/04/02/tom-watson-hits-out-at-hard-left-takeover-of-sandwell-councils-labour-group/ |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=[[The Express and Star]] |date=2 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2019 general election campaign===\n{{main|2019 United Kingdom general election}}\nFollowing the announcement of the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|12 December 2019 snap general election]], Momentum called for a large mobilisation of Momentum and Labour members.<ref name=\"LL-largecall\">{{cite web |last1=Rodgers |first1=Sienna |title=Momentum hosts \"largest mobilising call in UK political history\" with Corbyn |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/10/momentum-hosts-largest-mobilising-call-in-uk-political-history-with-corbyn/ |website=[[LabourList]] |accessdate=4 November 2019 |date=30 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\">{{cite news |last1=Eaton |first1=George |authorlink1=George Eaton |title=Inside Momentum: \"We\u2019re going to be here long after Jeremy Corbyn and I are dead\" |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/12/inside-momentum-we-re-going-be-here-long-after-jeremy-corbyn-and-i-are-dead |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=[[New Statesman]] |date=4 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The group increased their number of paid staff from 13 to 56 for the election campaign period.<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/> The group set a funding target of \u00a350,000 in 48 hours, however exceeded this and raised \u00a3100,000 in 12 hours.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peat |first1=Jack |title=Momentum raises \u00a3100,000 in 12 hours as it gears up for snap election |url=https://www.thelondoneconomic.com/politics/momentum-raises-100000-in-12-hours-as-it-gears-up-for-snap-election/30/10/ |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=[[The London Economic]] |date=30 October 2019}}</ref> Within six days of this funding drive Momentum have raised \u00a3255,000 from 10,000 individual donations, averaging at \u00a326 per donation which came close to beating the amount raised during the entirety of the 2017 General election campaign.<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\">{{cite news |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |title=Momentum seeks 'Labour legends' to take a week off to campaign |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/04/labours-momentum-raises-250000-in-six-days-to-fight-election |accessdate=4 November 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 November 2019}}</ref> Within 10 days, the group reached over \u00a3300,000 from 11,000 donations. Parker commented on these funds saying the organisation will be able to \"scale up every aspect of our operation from the get-go, which will allow us to deliver a campaign like nothing this country has ever seen before.\u201d<ref name=\"I-300k\">{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=Nigel |title=Momentum raises \u00a3300,000 for election campaign, dwarfing funds last time round |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/general-election-2019-momentum-jeremy-corbyn-labour-party-919594 |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=[[i (newspaper)|i]] |language=en}}</ref>\n\nMomentum created different tools and initiatives to help activists to organise. Prior to the campaign in September Momentum created a website \"Univotes\" to help students strategically plan which constituency is better for them to vote in; as students can register at both their home address and student address. The student vote been cited by Momentum as why Labour won in [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]], [[Warwick and Leamington (UK Parliament constituency)|Warwick and Leamington]], [[Portsmouth South (UK Parliament constituency)|Portsmouth South]], [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]] and [[Lincoln (UK Parliament constituency)|Lincoln]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lo |first1=Joe |title=Vote at home or at uni? Momentum launches tool for students to decide |url=https://leftfootforward.org/2019/09/vote-at-home-or-at-uni-momentum-launches-tool-for-students-to-decide/ |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=[[Left Foot Forward]] |date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |title=Momentum launches digital tool to help students register to vote |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/13/momentum-launches-digital-tool-to-help-students-register-to-vote |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=12 September 2019}}</ref> They created a website \"mycampaignmap.com\"- as a successor the to the 'My Nearest Marginal' website used for the 2017 election- which helps activists to coordinate their efforts in areas they are most needed.<ref name=\"LL-largecall\"/> My Campaign Map was used to organise over 21,000 events for the election period,<ref name=\"WiredMCM2019\">{{cite web |last1=Clarke |first1=Laurie |title=Inside Momentum's data-driven march to put Corbyn in Number 10 |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/momentum-labour-party-my-campaign-map |publisher=[[Wired UK]] |accessdate=4 December 2019 |date=30 November 2019}}</ref> and had over 170,000 unique visitors.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/>\n\nMomentum created a new type of volunteers called \"Labour Legends\", who took time off from work and commit at least a full week of campaigning in their area, or to volunteer in other constituencies.<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\"/> In 10 days this initiative acquired over 1,000 people have signed up, providing 40,000 volunteer hours,<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\">{{cite news |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |title=Momentum scales up for 'once-in-a-generation chance' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/19/momentum-scales-up-for-once-in-a-generation-chance |accessdate=25 November 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=19 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Vice-secretweapon\">{{cite news |title=Inside Momentum, Labour's Secret Weapon |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/a35me4/momentum-corbyn-labour-election-2019 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |author= Ruby Lott-Lavigna |work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |date=18 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and eventually rising to over 1,400 people getting involved,<ref name=\"WiredMCM2019\"/><ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/> 500 of which were allocated to marginal seats.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/> Momentum additionally encourages Labour party members abroad in Europe, The United States and Australia to register British expats to vote and to participate in phone banking from where they live.<ref name=\"GU-DSAsupport\">{{cite web |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |title=Labour gets support from Bernie Sanders campaigners in US |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/26/labour-gets-support-from-bernie-sanders-campaigners-in-us |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=4 December 2019 |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe group developed their campaign strategy with three principles in mind, according to Emma Rees: people power, the targeting of marginal seats, and the idea of getting everybody to step up. This was done by following a [[Decentralization|decentralised model]] in which activists have both a clear understanding of the aims and taking on organisational roles.<ref name=\"Jacobin-makeCorbynPM2019\">{{cite news |last1=Doherty |first1=Alex |title=Momentum Activists Are Trying to Make Jeremy Corbyn Prime Minister |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2019/11/momentum-labour-party-emma-rees-election |date=13 November 2019 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |work=[[Jacobin (magazine)|Jacobin]]}}</ref> Momentum has created several opportunities for activists to get involved in other ways of promotion- these include \u201cLet\u2019s Go\u201d teams who communicate on do phone banking using [[Whatsapp]], volunteers who watch through interviews of Conservative and Liberal Democrat politicians to be used for videos<ref name=\"GU-Onceinageneration2019\"/> and also people creating videos of themselves explaining why they are voting labour and posting them on social media to help engage with voters on all available platforms.<ref name=\"I-300k\"/>\n\nMomentum used social media advertising to encourage people to register to vote for the election. One of their adverts targeted [[Urdu]] speakers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volpicelli |first1=Gian |title=The Facebook election fight is now between the Tories and Momentum |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/facebook-adverts-general-election-momentum |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=[[Wired UK]] |date=29 November 2019}}</ref> The organising group controversially made a video for twitter based on a [[Coca-Cola]] Christmas advert that circulates every year. They were asked to cease and desist by the Coca-Cola company and the advertisement was taken down.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tidy |first1=Joe |title=Row over Labour group's use of famous Coca-Cola ad |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50520783 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=22 November 2019}}</ref> By the end of the election, their videos had a combined viewing of 106 million, double that of the last election.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\"/>\n\nIn 2020 Momentum submitted a report to the Labour party's \"Labour Together Review\", which was a cross-factional analysis of the party's performance and strategy, making several recommendations on the tools and approach for future elections.<ref name=\"mntm&labtogether\">{{cite web |title=Momentum Submission to the Labour Together Review of the 2019 General Election |url=https://peoplesmomentum.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Momentums-Labour-Together-Submission.pdf |publisher=Momentum |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Labour leadership elections and recent campaigning ===\nFollowing defeat in the 2019 general election in which Labour lost 60 seats, Jeremy Corbyn and Momentum's national coordinator Laura Parker resigned.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/22/insults-infighting-battle-lines-drawn-future-labour-party|title= Labour: anger, recrimination and bitterness mark fresh battle for party\u2019s soul |last= Helm|first= Tom |publisher= [[The Guardian]] |date= 22 December 2019 |accessdate= 12 January 2020}}</ref> Corbyn's triggered a [[2020 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|leadership election]], which was coupled with the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|deputy leadership election]], with the results to be unveiled for both in April 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Who will be Labour's next leader? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50781341 |accessdate=16 December 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Rowena |last2=Pidd |first2=Helen |title=Labour leadership race begins as senior figures back Rebecca Long-Bailey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/15/labour-leadership-race-begins-as-senior-figures-back-rebecca-long-bailey |accessdate=16 December 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=15 December 2019}}</ref> On 14 January Momentum ran a 2 day online consultation with their members whether to endorse [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] for leader and [[Angela Rayner]] for deputy leader. The closed format of the consultation was controversial.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cowburn |first1=Ashley |title=Momentum faces backlash over \u2018ludicrous\u2019 Labour leadership ballot of members |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-leadership-momentum-member-ballot-deputy-candidates-a9283826.html |publisher=[[The Independent]] |language=en |date=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bartlett |first1=Nicola |title=Momentum slammed for only giving members one option on Labour leadership ballot |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/backlash-after-momentum-sends-members-21283993 |accessdate=16 January 2020 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=15 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> 7,395 members participated with 70% supporting Long-Bailey and 52% supporting Rayner.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chappell |first1=Elliot |title=Momentum back Long-Bailey and Rayner after member ballot |url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/momentum-backs-long-bailey-and-rayner-after-members-ballot/ |publisher=[[LabourList]] |accessdate=17 January 2020 |date=16 January 2020}}</ref> Momentum planned hundreds of phone banking events to support Long-Bailey.<ref>{{cite news |last1=editor |first1=Rowena Mason Deputy political |title=Labour must stir up democratic revolution to win power, says Long-Bailey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/16/labour-must-stir-up-democratic-revolution-to-win-power-says-long-bailey |accessdate=17 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 January 2020}}</ref> Keir Starmer won the election in the first round - with Long-Bailey wining 28% of the vote - and Momentum failed to win any of the NEC by elections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52164589|title=Keir Starmer elected as new Labour leader|date=2020-04-04|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/apr/04/labour-leadership-election-winner-keir-starmer-long-bailey-nandy-and-jeremy-corbyns-successor-to-be-announced-at-1045am-live-news|title=Keir Starmer elected Labour leader with 56% of vote on first round \u2014 as it happened|date=2020-04-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In response to his victory, Momentum congratulated him and positioned themselves as challenging and working with the new leadership to push for 'transformational policies'.<ref name=\"PH-Keirwon\">{{cite news |last1=Schofield |first1=Kevin |title=Momentum vows to 'hold Keir Starmer to account' after Labour left suffers heavy defeats |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/momentum-vows-to-hold-keir-starmer-to-account-after-labour-left-suffers-heavy-defeats |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=[[PoliticsHome]] |date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nLeading to the [[2020 United Kingdom local elections|2020 local elections]], the [[London Labour Party]] changed its selection process for [[London Assembly#Assembly members|assembly members]] so that party members select new candidates. Four assembly members were standing down leading up to the election. This was believed to be an opportunity for Momentum, who have gained influence in the regional party in 2018 regional conference elections,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://labourlist.org/2019/03/labour-left-sweeps-the-london-regional-board/ |title= Labour left sweeps the London regional board |author= Sienna Rodgers |publisher= [[LabourList]] |date= 3 March 2019 |accessdate= 19 March 2019}}</ref> to put up candidates so they can push [[Sadiq Khan]]'s election manifesto to the left.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/05/labour-london-aembly-members-face-reselection-fight |title= Labour London assembly members face reselection fight |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 5 November 2018 |accessdate= 5 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/momentum-bids-to-push-sadiq-khan-manifesto-to-left-a4092731.html |title= Momentum bids to push Sadiq Khan manifesto to Left |author= Sophia Sleigh |newspaper= [[London Evening Standard]] |date= 16 March 2019 |accessdate= 17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Issues and other campaigning ==\n=== Austerity ===\nOne of Momentum's primary objectives was to create an anti-austerity movement in the UK connected to the Labour Party.<ref name=\"BBC-Mmtmcivilwar2017\"/> In particular, Momentum criticised Osborne's proposal to cut [[tax credit]] payments for working families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noworkpenalty.peoplesmomentum.com/|title=No Work Penalty|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/a-b59a-Momentums-potential-to-unify-and-energise-political-campaigning|title=Momentum\u2019s potential to unify and energise political campaigning|author=Steve Sweeney|newspaper=Morning Star|date=24 October 2015|accessdate=3 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, local Momentum groups started to collect and volunteer for food banks.<ref name=\"theguardian2\"/>\n\n=== Syria bombing ===\nMomentum called for its membership to lobby Labour MPs \"to support Corbyn, not Cameron, over Syria\" on [[Twitter]], linking to the [[Stop the War Coalition]]'s Don't Bomb Syria campaign which opposed the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government's proposal to extend its bombing sorties against [[Daesh]] (also known as ISIS) from Daesh-held territory in Iraq to also cover Daesh-held territory in Syria. Corbyn had argued that Cameron's government lacked a credible plan for defeating Daesh and that the bombing in Syria would not increase the United Kingdom's national security. Corbyn has also stated his view that military action should always be a last resort. Some Labour MPs criticised Momentum's move to lobby on party political grounds before the Labour party's official position on military action had been decided, with [[Gavin Shuker]] asking: \"Who decided this was your position on Syria, and to lobby MPs in this way?\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dathan|first1=Matt|title=Jeremy Corbyn campaign group urges Labour MPs to reject air strikes in Syria|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-campaign-group-urges-labour-mps-to-reject-air-strikes-in-syria-a6745141.html|accessdate=23 November 2015|newspaper=Independent|date=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Bankrupt Climate Change ===\nIn March 2019, Momentum started a campaign called Bankrupt Climate Change, a direct action campaign protesting outside of [[Barclays]]' banks in 40 different local groups. The campaign's objective is to raise awareness for Barclays bank investing in fossil fuel companies.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/30/john-mcdonnell-backs-momentum-on-barclays-protest |title= John McDonnell backs Momentum on Barclays protest |author= Damien Gayle |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 30 March 2019 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/17530689.bradford-momentum-branch-to-stage-city-centre-climate-change-protest/ |title= Bradford Momentum branch to stage city centre climate change protest |author= Felicity Macnamara |publisher= [[Telegraph and Argus]] |date= 28 March 2019 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref> They reference a report says that Barclays as the largest financer in Europe and sixth in the world for financing the fossil fuel companies.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://bright-green.org/2019/03/21/momentum-members-joins-fight-against-barclays-fossil-fuel-funding/ |title= Momentum members join fight against Barclays\u2019 fossil fuel funding |author= Chris Saltmarsh |publisher= [[Bright Green]] |date= 21 March 2019 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Antisemitism allegations ===\nSince 2015, there have been a series of allegations of antisemitism against Labour Party members. Many leading figures in Momentum were Jewish or of Jewish heritage, such as  Klug,<ref name=\"JC-Momentumsojewish\"/> Lansman,<ref name=\"GU-Lansmanproblems2019\"/> Schneider,<ref name=\"JC-Momentumsojewish\"/> Rhea Wolfson<ref name=\"FT-insidethebeast\">{{cite news |last1=Judah |first1=Ben |title=Momentum: inside Labour\u2019s revolutionary movement |url=https://www.ft.com/content/0e99fc98-4872-11e8-8ae9-4b5ddcca99b3 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=27 April 2018}}</ref> and [[Jackie Walker (activist)|Jackie Walker]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mortimer|first=Caroline|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/anti-semitism-row-momentum-organiser-jackie-walker-readmitted-to-labour-party-following-racism-a7053966.html|title=Anti-Semitism row: Momentum organiser Jackie Walker readmitted to Labour party following racism allegations|work=[[The Independent]]|date=28 May 2016|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> Walker, Momentum's vice-chair, was expelled from the Labour Party for behaviour related to allegations of antisemitism.<ref>Jessica Elgot: [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/27/labour-expels-jackie-walker-for-leaked-antisemitism-comments ''Labour expels Jackie Walker for leaked antisemitism remarks'']. The Guardian, 27 March 2019</ref> In April 2018, Joshua Garfield, a Jewish youth officer in a Momentum branch in London, resigned from his role because, he says, antisemitism from members of the branch was making him feel \"sometimes unsafe and certainly untrusted\".<ref name=\"JC-Momentumsojewish\"/><ref>https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-momentum-organiser-resigns-over-deep-seated-prejudices-in-local-branch/</ref><ref>https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jewish-labour-party-momentum-antisemitism-joshua-garfield-newham-atrociously-offensive-1.462137</ref> Garfield was a member and later officer of the [[Jewish Labour Movement]] who appeared in the [[Panorama (TV programme)|Panorama]] programme on antisemitism in the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/joshua-garfield-selected-as-labour-s-candidate-against-tory-chairman-james-cleverley-1.490814|title=BBC Panorama whistleblower selected as Labour's candidate against Tory Chairman James Cleverley|date=29 October 2019|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nMomentum itself has also had issues with individual members<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-antisemitism-momentum-barnet-jews-jeremy-corbyn-israel-a8473501.html |title= Momentum activists accused of 'anti-Zionist ranting' in Labour antisemitism row |author= Benjamin Kentish |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 1 August 2018 |accessdate= 17 July 2019}}</ref> and have accepted that some Labour members have expressed antisemitism,<ref name=\"JC-Momentumsojewish\">{{cite news|url= https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/momentum-is-so-jewish-claims-leading-labour-activist-1.463274|title= Momentum \u2018is so Jewish\u2019 claims leading Labour activist |author= Lee Harpin |newspaper= [[The Jewish Chronicle]] |date= 30 April 2018 |accessdate= 17 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/antisemitism-labour-jeremy-corbyn-smears-momentum-a8285656.html |title= Antisemitism in Labour cannot be dismissed as smears, say Momentum |author= Andrew Woodcock |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 2 April 2018 |accessdate= 17 July 2019}}</ref> with Lansman attributing this to \"conspiracy theorists\" joining.<ref name=\"GU-Lansmanproblems2019\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/25/labour-has-widespread-problem-with-antisemitism-momentum-founder-jon-lansman |title= Labour has widespread problem with antisemitism \u2013 Momentum founder |author= Seth Jacobson |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 25 February 2019 |accessdate= 16 July 2019}}</ref> Such [[List of conspiracy theories#Antisemitic conspiracy theories|antisemitic conspiracy theories]] have been challenged by Momentum through viral videos.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://twitter.com/PeoplesMomentum/status/1101143739588923392?s=20 |title= The conspiracy behind conspiracy theories |author= |publisher= Momentum |date= 28 February 2019 |accessdate= 17 July 2019}}</ref> In the 2018 NEC elections, Momentum withdrew their support for [[Peter Willsman]] after an NEC meeting in which he described some of those \"lecturing\" the party about antisemitism as \"Trump fanatics\" who were \"making up duff information without any evidence at all\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-nec-member-pete-willsman-threatened-to-do-in-momentum-chief-jon-lansman-1.480869 |title= Labour NEC member Pete Willsman threatened to 'do in' Momentum chief Jon Lansman |newspaper= [[The Jewish Chronicle]] |date= 3 March 2019 |accessdate= 16 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/jul/31/corbyn-ally-says-jewish-trump-fanatics-make-up-antisemitism-claims |title= Corbyn ally says 'Jewish Trump fanatics making up' antisemitism claims |author= Verity Bowman and Pippa Crerar |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 31 July 2018 |accessdate= 25 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Brexit ===\nOfficially, Momentum has maintained a neutral position of the European Union and the prospect of a second referendum, instead supporting the party's position.<ref name=\"GU-Radicalmomentum\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/may/16/momentum-urges-labour-to-adopt-radical-pledges-in-next-manifesto |title= Momentum urges Labour to adopt 'radical' pledges in next manifesto |author= Heather Stewart |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 16 May 2019 |accessdate= 16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever several members of Momentum have [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|supported a second referendum]] with remain and the government's deal as options. In June 2018, the [[People's Vote]] campaign group was launched and included several former Momentum figures as well as trade union leaders. The group's launch statement was signed by [[Transport Salaried Staffs' Association|TSSA]] union general secretary [[Manuel Cortes]], economist [[Ann Pettifor]], former Momentum steering group member Michael Chessum and former CWU general secretary [[Billy Hayes (trade unionist)|Billy Hayes]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Elgot | first = Jessica | title = Pro-Corbyn group to launch drive for public vote on Brexit deal | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jun/25/pro-corbyn-group-to-launch-drive-peoples-vote-on-final-brexit-deal-labour | work = The Guardian | date = 25 June 2018 | access-date = 20 August 2018}}</ref> Polling of Momentum members in November 2018 found a majority supporting such a referendum<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-latest-momentum-labour-referendum-deal-corbyn-theresa-may-eu-a8621431.html |title= Brexit: Corbyn under pressure as Momentum members back referendum on Theresa May's deal |author= Benjamin Kentish |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 6 November 2018 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref> The left-wing, pro-European pressure group [[Another Europe Is Possible]] features Momentum members,<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/elections/2018/09/factions-fudge-and-fashion-how-momentum-went-mainstream |title= Factions, fudge and fashion: How Momentum went mainstream |author= Anoosh Chakelian |magazine= [[New Statesman]] |date= 26 September 2018 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref> such as former steering committee member Michael Chessum.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/10/new-leftwing-coalition-urges-labour-to-reject-brexit |title= New leftwing coalition urges Labour to reject Brexit |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 10 December 2018 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref> In March 2019 188 Momentum activists sent an open letter to Lansman to support a second referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://labourlist.org/2019/03/join-put-it-to-the-people-demo-momentum-activists-tell-jon-lansman/?amp |title= Join \u2018Put it to the People\u2019 demo, Momentum activists tell Jon Lansman |author= Sienna Rodgers |publisher= [[Labour List]] |date= 22 March 2019 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Reselection of MPs ===\nCritics of Corbyn within the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] have raised a concern that Momentum may encourage the [[deselection]] of MPs and councillors who disagree with it, in a process called mandatory reselection, in which all Labour politicians would be subject to internal elections.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wintour|first1=Patrick|title=Activists to harness Corbyn campaign energy with Momentum |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/08/activists-to-harness-corbyn-campaign-energy-with-momentum|accessdate=25 October 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=8 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/len-mcluskey-jeremy-corbyn-labour-party-leadership-contest-len-mccluskey-unite-deselect-mps-clive-a7315636.html |title= Union boss hints disloyal Labour MPs could be deselected after leadership election |author= Caroline Mortimer|newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 19 September 2016 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref> In 2015 Momentum denied this claim, saying \"we will not campaign for the deselection of any MP and will not permit any local Momentum groups to do so. The selection of candidates is entirely a matter for local party members and rightly so\".<ref name=\"BBC-WorriedMPs\"/><ref>{{cite news|title = The 66 Labour MPs who voted for Syria air strikes face threats of deselection and branded 'warmongers'|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-mps-who-backed-syria-air-strikes-hit-back-after-jeremy-corbyn-supporters-threaten-deselection-a6758656.html|website = The Independent <!--|date = 15 July-->|date = 3 December 2015}}</ref> The organization is however supportive of open selections, in which all members have equal influence on the selection process and are more democratically accountable rather than just socialist societies and trade unions having a strong say.<ref name=\"BBC-LPDR\"/>\n\nIn July 2018 Momentum's national coordinator Laura Parker advocated that four Labour MPs who voted down an opposition amendment to the [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018|EU withdrawal bill]] to feature a Customs Union, in line with the government, should be deselected. At the 2018 Labour Conference, Momentum's reselection reforms were supported by Corbyn.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-labour-mp-deselection-momentum-nec-vote-conference-a8521141.html |title= Jeremy Corbyn backs Momentum calls for 'changes' that could make it easier to deselect Labour MPs |author= Benjamin Kentish |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 3 September 2018 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, Momentum announced they would support Labour and Momentum members wishing to challenge sitting Labour MPs. The aim has been to encourage a younger, more [[working class]] and ethnically diverse selection of Labour MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/12/momentum-drive-labour-members-deselect-mps |title= Momentum announces drive to help Labour members deselect MPs |author= Jessica Elgot |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 12 July 2019 |accessdate= 15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Labour Party Democracy Review ===\nFrom 2017, the Labour Party consulted on a democracy review that would see the membership gain greater voting capabilities. Momentum has been an advocate of both greater membership involvement in party decision making and in their view \"bolder reforms\".<ref name=\"BBC-LPDR\">{{cite news|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-45562446 |title= Labour's democracy review - how democratic is it? |author= Iain Watson |work= [[BBC News]] |date= 18 September 2018 |accessdate= 29 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"GU-shelvedDR\"/> Momentum has pushed for the lowering of nomination threshold for a candidate in Labour leadership elections. This is so a left-wing successor to Corbyn could contest any future election easily.<ref name=\"GU-shelvedDR\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/18/corbyns-proposals-to-transform-labour-party-parked-for-a-year |title= Corbyn's proposals to transform Labour party parked for a year |author= Heather Stewart and Jessica Elgot |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 18 September 2018 |accessdate= 20 March 2019}}</ref> The Group also supports member election council leaders.<ref name=\"Indie-tinkering\">{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-labour-party-reforms-jon-lansman-jeremy-corbyn-nec-plp-mp-a8420806.html |title= Momentum chief dismisses Labour reform proposals as 'tinkering around the edges' |author= Joe Watts |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= 28 June 2018 |accessdate= 30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nMomentum tabled plans to update the way the NEC's BAME representative is chosen, with a [[one member, one vote]] election replacing the current system where a small party group decides the post. Under the group's plans, all black or minority ethnic members of the party would automatically become part of [[BAME Labour]] and have one member, one vote rights in electing their NEC representative. BAME Labour would also have an independent organisation, with its committee having direct access to its own membership list and centrally-funded finances and the ability to organise its own campaigns and events independently.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite news |last=Waugh|first=Paul|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/keith-vaz-facing-defeat-as-momentum-submits-plan-for-omov-bame-labour-reform-young-labour-autonomy-too_uk_5a58b7d0e4b02cebbfdb09ac|title=Keith Vaz Facing Loss Of Labour NEC Seat As Momentum Urges More Voting Power For Minority Ethnic Members|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nCrucial votes regarding the Democracy Review took place during the [[Labour Party Conference (UK)#2017 Brighton|2017 Labour Party Conference]] in Brighton. Momentum launched ''M.app'', a smartphone app to alert delegates to timings of key votes on the national conference floor as well as send real-time information about events and rallies.<ref name=\"theguardian3\">{{cite news |last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/21/momentum-to-launch-app-to-get-its-voters-out-at-labour-conference|title=Momentum to launch app to get its voters out at Labour conference|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 September 2017|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> The compromise motion of lowering the threshold required of local branches and local union branches to express dissatisfaction in an MP's performance from 50% to 33% passed.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Elgot | first1 = Jessica | last2 = Syal | first2 = Rajeev |title= Labour members in open revolt at union-backed party rule changes |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/23/labour-members-in-open-revolt-at-union-backed-party-reforms |work= [[The Guardian]] |date= 23 September 2018 |accessdate= 24 September 2018}}</ref> However it was announced that the democracy review was being shelved.<ref name=\"GU-shelvedDR\"/>\n\n=== Elections to Labour's Executive Committees ===\nIn the 2016 elections for the [[National Executive Committee of the Labour Party|National Executive Committee]], it emerged that Momentum, alongside the [[Centre-Left Grassroots Alliance]] and the [[Campaign for Labour Party Democracy]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pope|first1=Conor|title=Left slate in poll position for NEC race after late spate of nominations|url=http://labourlist.org/2016/07/left-slate-in-poll-position-for-nec-race-after-late-spate-of-nominations/|website=LabourList|accessdate=16 July 2016|date=16 July 2016}}</ref> were jointly backing six representatives for the [[National Executive Committee of the Labour Party|National Executive Committee]] (NEC), namely Rhea Wolfson, the former chair of the Jewish Society who replaced [[Ken Livingstone]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Doherty|first1=Rosa|title=Former Jewish Society chair backed to replace Ken Livingstone on Labour executive|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/157983/former-jewish-society-chair-backed-replace-ken-livingstone-labour-executive|accessdate=16 July 2016|work=Jewish Chronicle|date=10 May 2016}}</ref> [[Christine Shawcroft]], a senior figure in Momentum who had been a member of the NEC for fifteen years and had been briefly suspended from the party after defending [[Lutfur Rahman (politician)|Lutfur Rahman]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Syal|first1=Rajeev|title=Labour veteran suspended from party for supporting Lutfur Rahman|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/11/labour-christine-shawcroft-suspended-lutfur-rahman-tower-hamlets|accessdate=16 July 2016|work=The Guardian|date=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Cooper\">{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Charlie|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-momentum-national-executive-committee-elections-labour-party-a6930871.html|title=Jeremy Corbyn supporters urged to use Labour NEC elections to cement his hold on party|work=The Independent|date=14 March 2016|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> gaining media attention after jocular comments about dialogue with [[Daesh]] instead of [[air strikes]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Riley-Smith|first1=Ben|title=British soldiers should have 'cups of tea' with Islamic State terrorists, says Jeremy Corbyn ally|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12199570/British-soldiers-should-have-cups-of-tea-with-Islamic-State-terrorists-says-Jeremy-Corbyn-ally.html|accessdate=16 July 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=20 March 2016}}</ref> [[Peter Willsman]], [[Claudia Webbe]], [[Ann Black]], and Darren Williams.<ref name=\"Cooper\"/> All six of the candidates were elected to the six available places.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/momentum-backed-candidates-sweep-labour-8590476|title=Momentum-backed candidates sweep Labour ruling NEC elections in boost for Corbyn|first=Mikey|last=Smith|date=8 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Momentum and [[Campaign for Socialism]], their Scottish sister organisation, won 5 our of eight of the seats on the Executive Committee in [[Scottish Labour]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jamieson |first1=David |title=Momentum activists hail shift to more \"radical\" Scottish Labour with victories on executive |url=https://www.commonspace.scot/articles/10253/momentum-activists-hail-shift-more-radical-scottish-labour-victories-executive |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=[[CommonSpace]] |date=3 February 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2017 labour conference, it was announced that Labour would add three more member-elected spaces on the NEC, in response to the significant rise in membership. During the ballot period, [[Peter Willsman]] was removed from Momentum's list of recommended candidates following an allegation of antisemitism. Willsman had been recorded as describing some Jewish critics of Labour as  \"Trump fanatics\".<ref>{{cite news | last = Heffer | first = Greg | title = Jeremy Corbyn told to 'expel' ally Peter Willsman over anti-Semitism rant | url = https://news.sky.com/story/jeremy-corbyn-told-to-expel-ally-peter-willsman-over-anti-semitism-rant-11455287 | work = Sky News | date = 1 August 2018 | access-date = 2 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1= Crerar |first1= Pippa |last2= Marsh |first2= Sarah |title= Antisemitism row: Momentum drops Peter Willsman from NEC re-election list |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/01/antisemitism-row-momentum-drops-peter-willsman-from-nec-re-election-list |work= The Guardian |date= 1 August 2018 |access-date= 2 August 2018}}</ref> Three other Momentum-backed candidates were elected onto the Labour Party's NEC, namely Jon Lansman, Yasmine Dar and Rachel Garnham.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goodall|first1=Lewis|title=Crucial National Executive Committee vote transforms Labour's future|url=https://news.sky.com/story/crucial-national-executive-committee-vote-transforms-labours-future-11209060|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=Sky News|date=15 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mason|first1=Rowena|last2=Elgot|first2=Jessica|last3=Syal|first3=Rajeev|title=Momentum founder elected to NEC calls for Labour transformation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/15/momentum-backed-candidates-elected-labour-national-executive-committee|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=15 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Forsyth|first1=James|title=What does Momentum\u2019s NEC clean sweep mean for Labour?|url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2018/01/what-does-momentums-nec-clean-sweep-mean-for-labour/|website=Coffee House|publisher=The Spectator|accessdate=17 January 2018|date=15 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Momentum founder voted on to Labour NEC|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-42688288|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=BBC News|date=15 January 2018}}</ref> In April 2020, Momentum put up three candidates- two for two casual vacancies and one for a newly created BAME positionion. None of these candidates were successful.<ref name=\"PH-Keirwon\"/>\n\n== The World Transformed ==\n{{main|The World Transformed}}\nStarting in 2016, Momentum began a four-day festival called The World Transformed alongside the [[Labour Party Conference (UK)|Labour Party conference]] featuring art, music and culture alongside political discussions.<ref name=\"NS-unfinishedrev2019\"/><ref name=\"Huck-TWT\">{{cite web|url= https://www.huckmag.com/perspectives/opinion-perspectives/the-world-transformed/ |title= Why The World Transformed is the future of British politics |author= Nathan Akehurst |publisher= [[Huck magazine]] |date= 27 September 2017 |accessdate= 25 February 2019}}</ref> This started with the Liverpool conference in 2016. One event featured a debate between [[Caroline Lucas]] co-leader of the [[Green Party of England and Wales]], [[Compass (think tank)|Compass]] chair [[Neal Lawson]] and [[Jon Lansman]] and Rhea Wolfson of Momentum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/sep/29/labour-party-of-the-future-labour-conference-momentum|title=A Labour party of the future is beginning to emerge|date=29 September 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref> In ''[[The Times]]'', [[Tony Blair]]'s former speech writer [[Philip Collins (journalist)|Philip Collins]] was positive about the event, compared to the Labour conference, \"harnessed and embraced, Momentum could be a force for good\", but wrote \"the only thing wrong with their slogan 'Jez We Can' is the first word\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Philip|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/momentum-can-be-labours-unlikely-saviour-tsd2r3ltt|title=Momentum can be Labour\u2019s unlikely saviour|work=The Times|date=29 September 2016|accessdate=10 October 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nThe World Transformed spanned nine venues across Brighton, where the Labour Party 2017 Conference was held. Many MPs attended, including [[Jeremy Corbyn]], [[John McDonnell]], [[Diane Abbott]], [[Emily Thornberry]] and [[Ed Miliband]].\n\nThe 2018 festival at the Liverpool conference had the capacity for 10,000 people to attend.<ref name=\"Sky-TWT2018\">{{cite web | last = Allegretti | first = Aubrey |title= The World Transformed: How Momentum festival is challenging for the 'mainstream' Labour conference |url= https://news.sky.com/story/the-world-transformed-how-momentum-festival-is-challenging-for-the-mainstream-labour-conference-11505328 |publisher= [[Sky News]] |date= 23 September 2018 |accessdate= 24 September 2018}}</ref> Speakers include [[2017 French presidential election|2017 French presidential candidate]] [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]] as a key-note speaker,<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/23/jean-luc-melenchon-to-speak-at-pro-corbyn-event-in-liverpool |title= Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon to speak at pro-Corbyn event in Liverpool |author= Angelique Chrisafis |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 23 September 2018 |accessdate= 24 September 2018}}</ref> as well as Jeremy Corbyn, [[Katja Kipping]] (leader of [[The Left (Germany)|Die Linke]]), [[Ralf Stegner]] ([[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]]), [[Zitto Kabwe]] (leader of [[Alliance for Change and Transparency]]) and [[Ash Sarkar]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Rodgers | first = Sienna |title= The World Transformed reveals full line-up ahead of Labour conference |url= https://labourlist.org/2018/08/the-world-transformed-reveals-full-line-up-ahead-of-labour-conference/ |publisher= [[LabourList]] |date= 8 August 2018 |accessdate= 24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Constitution and structure ==\nIn the original formation of Momentum, it used a delegate system on an executive board known as the steering committee. In late October 2016, the steering committee voted to adopt to [[One member, one vote]] (OMOV) done only on a digital instead of the delegate system- it was controversial with some on the committee and didn't pass.<ref name=\"TG-radical2016\">{{cite news|last=Gilligan|first=Andrew|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12156177/momentum-activists-jeremy-corbyn-labour-purge.html|title=Revealed: The radical hard-Left Momentum activists mounting a ruthless purge of Labour|work=The Sunday Telegraph|date=13 February 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NS-Corbynplzintervene\">{{cite news|last=Bush|first=Stephen|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/12/jeremy-corbyn-urged-intervene-momentums-feud|title=Jeremy Corbyn urged to intervene in Momentum's feud|work=New Statesman|date=6 December 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GU-Lansmanvows2016\">{{cite news |last=Syal|first=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/dec/08/corbyn-ally-vows-fight-control-momentum-labour|title=Jon Lansman vows stay in Momentum|work=The Guardian|date=8 December 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-Mmtmcivilwar2017\">{{cite news|last=Lobel|first=Mark|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38258143|title=Is Momentum at war with itself?|work=BBC News|date=9 December 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> However, a new constitution was announced on 11 January 2017 including OMOV. New members of Momentum were now required to also be members of the Labour Party, with existing Momentum members being given until July to join.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-affiliated-labour-party-jeremy-corbyn-members-must-join-a7520626.html|title=Momentum pushes activists to join Labour party to retain membership under new constitution|work=The Independent|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> Lansman initiated changes via an email. After managing to convince the steering committee, he abolished the national committee and replaced it with a Labour-only national coordinating group (NCG).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=Heather|last2=Syal|first2=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/10/momentum-shakeup-will-force-members-to-join-labour|title=Momentum shakeup will force members to join Labour|work=The Guardian|date=10 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Silvera|first=Ian|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/jon-lansman-accused-coup-momentum-unveils-new-rules-plan-join-labour-1600356|title=Jon Lansman accused of 'coup' as Momentum unveils new rules and plan to join Labour|work=International Business Times|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> A new online model of organisation without a regional structure was created with the specific intention of preventing [[far-left]] entryists dominating delegated meetings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pettitt|first=Robin|url=http://www.democraticaudit.com/2017/03/07/losing-momentum-the-power-struggles-that-are-hobbling-the-corbyn-movement/|title=Losing Momentum? The power struggles that are hobbling the Corbyn movement|work=Democratic Audit UK|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> Lansman resigned as a director of Momentum on 12 January, being replaced by Christine Shawcroft, in order to stand for election to the steering committee, it was reported.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gartside|first=Ben|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment-analysis/2017/01/12/jon-lansman-s-resignation-won-t-be-his-last-role-of-the-dice|title=Jon Lansman's resignation won't be his last role of the dice at Momentum|work=Politics|date=12 February 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Casalicchio|first1=Emilio |last2=Schofield|first2=Kevin|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/news/82279/blow-jon-lansman-his-own-momentum|title=Blow for Jon Lansman as his own Momentum branch votes against his 'coup'|work=Politics Home|date=12 January 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> The group in early March 2017 relaunched with its new constitutional structure, and a first meeting of the new NCG on 11 March and a conference on 25 March, both in Birmingham.<ref name=\"MacAskill\">{{cite news|last1=MacAskill|first1=Ewen|last2=Hacillo|first2=Alex|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/04/momentum-relaunch-factionalism-jon-lansman-labour|title=Momentum plans relaunch to end factional infighting|work=The Observer|date=4 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Membership ===\n{{Bar graph\n| title = Membership (by year)\n| float =   \n| bar_width = 20\n| width_units = em\n| data_max = 70000\n| label_type = Year\n| data_type = #\n| label1 = 2016<ref name=\"GU-Lansmanvows2016\"/> \n| data1 = 21,000\n| label2 = 2017<ref name=\"independent2\"/> \n| data2 = 31,000\n| label3 = 2018<ref name=\"GUmomuntrainscot\"/>\n| data3 = 42,000\n| label4 = 2019<ref name=\"Gu-LabLegends\"/>\n| data4 = 40,000\n}}\nIn 2015, the year of the group's formation, Momentum originally had 60,000 supporters who paid no subscription and 50 local groups organised.<ref name=\"BBC-WorriedMPs\">{{cite news|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34609114|title= What is Momentum, and why is it worrying Labour MPs?|author= Norman Smith |work= [[BBC News]] |date= 24 October 2015 |accessdate= 29 March 2019}}</ref> By September 2017 the organisation had grown to have 31,000 members across 170 local groups, with 15 members of staff.<ref name=\"independent2\">{{cite news |last=Farrell|first=Jeff|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/momentum-membership-jeremy-corbyn-labour-party-leader-supporters-a7988656.html|title=Momentum membership soars above 30,000 as Corbyn-supporting Labour group's influence grows|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=8 October 2017|accessdate=10 October 2017}}</ref> As of January 2018, the group had 35,000 members<ref name=\"theguardian4\">{{cite news |last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-members-growth-labour-party-jeremy-corbyn-ukip-green-conservative-membership-numbers-tory-a8166031.html/|title=Momentum surges past 35,000 members with \u2018more than 1,000 members joining every month\u2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref> With 15% membership increase since the start of 2018, by April the organisation had 40,000. Momentum has said that 95 per cent of its current funding comes from membership fees and small donations, with the average fee standing at \u00a33 a year.<ref name=\"Cowburn040418\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/momentum-membership-jeremy-corbyn-green-party-40000-labour-nec-jon-lansman-a8286706.html|title=Momentum: Corbyn-backing organisation now has 40,000 paying members, overtaking Green Party|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|date=4 April 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=4 April 2018|location=London}}</ref> In July 2018, it was reported that Momentum had 42,000 members with 92% (38,700) in England, 4% in Wales (2,000) and 3% in Scotland (1,300).<ref name=\"GUmomuntrainscot\">{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/26/momentum-heads-glasgow-first-scottish-training-event |title= Momentum heads to Glasgow to hold first Scottish training event |author= Libby Brooks |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 26 July 2018 |accessdate= 9 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nMomentum's membership base has been seen as being occupied by two types: young activists who joined the Labour Party during and after Corbyn's initial leadership election in 2015; and older veterens of the Labour Party left and [[far-left]] parties across Great Britain.<ref name=\"GU-Lansmanvows2016\"/><ref name=\"BBC-Mmtmcivilwar2017\"/><ref name=\"HP-Corbynsaysbenice\"/> In the original formation of Momentum, several members and activists [[Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition]], [[Left Unity (UK)|Left Unity]], the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]] (SWP), the [[Socialist Party (England and Wales)|Socialist Party]] and the [[Alliance for Workers' Liberty]] (AWL) might attach themselves to Momentum as a means to join the Labour Party.<ref name=\"TG-radical2016\"/> However, the shift in Momentum policy to only allow Labour and Momentum members to organise had a profound shift on this aspect.\n\n=== National Coordinating Group ===\nFollowing a January 2017 survey by Momentum to which over 40% of members responded, the organisation's steering committee voted by majority to introduce a new constitution.<ref name=\"Cowburn110117\"/> Eight Members' Representatives were elected: four for London and the South East; two for the Midlands, the East, the West and Wales; two for the North, Scotland and International; and four public office holders.<ref name=\"labourlist2\">{{cite news |last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|url=https://www.labourlist.org/2018/04/women-and-minorities-triumph-in-latest-momentum-election/|title=Women and minorities triumph in latest Momentum election|work= |location=London|publisher=Labour List|date=17 April 2018|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> 7,500 members took part in the election, or 34% of the membership.<ref name=\"NCGelec18\"/> In April 2018 a new set of elections took place with all four regional coordinating offices having four spaces. Over 13,000 votes were cast (35% of eligible members).<ref name=\"labourlist2\"/><ref name=\"NCGelec18\">{{cite web|url= https://peoplesmomentum.com/wp-content/uploads/Footer_Pages/Downloads/180417_NCG_Final_Results.pdf |title= National  Coordinating Group  Elections 2018 |publisher= Momentum |date= 17 April 2018 |accessdate= 2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe current composition is:<ref name=\"NCGelec18\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:95%;\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n|-\n! style=\"width=25%\" | London and the South East\n! style=\"width=25%\" | Midlands, the East, the West and Wales\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Collapsible list\n | <small>Apsana Begum</small>\n | <small>Becky Boumelha</small>\n | <small>[[Jon Lansman]]</small>\n | <small>Yannis Gourtsoyannis</small>\n}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Collapsible list\n | <small>Michael Thawe</small>\n | <small>Natasha Josette</small>\n | <small>Martin Menear</small>\n | <small>Cecile Wright</small>\n}}\n|-\n! style=\"width=25%\" | North, Scotland and International\n! style=\"width=25%\" | Public office holders\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Collapsible list\n | <small>Aneesa Akbar</small>\n | <small>Liz Smith</small>\n | <small>Elizabeth Hayden</small>\n | <small>John Taylor</small>\n}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{{Collapsible list\n | <small>Helen McDonald</small>\n | <small>Leigh Drennan</small>\n | <small>Joseph Ejiofor</small>\n | <small>Emina Ibrahim</small>\n}}\n|}\n\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Politics|United Kingdom|Socialism}}\n* [[Campaign for Labour Party Democracy]]\n* [[Compass (think tank)]]\n* [[Fabian Society]]\n* [[Political party affiliation in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Socialist Campaign Group]], MP grouping containing most Momentum supporting MPs\n* ''[[Tribune (magazine)|Tribune]]''\n* [[UK Uncut]]\n\n== References =